Unlike Canada, the US Federal States are responsible for holding elections in the individual states.
In this sense, since 2009, the majority of American governments have proclaimed new laws that make it difficult to register or vote.
This phenomenon has gained in importance after the November 2010 elections, with 675 new Republican representatives in 26 states.
As a result, 180 draft laws were introduced in 2011 alone, limiting the exercise of electoral law in 41 states.
The new electoral laws require voters to present a photo ID and proof of U.S. citizenship.
In addition, these laws also shorten the time periods for early voting, declare the right invalid to register as voters on election day, and deny citizens the right to vote for which a court file exists.
Before the 2006 elections, no US state asked voters to present a photo ID.
Indiana was the first state to make such a demand.
The United States Supreme Court confirmed the constitutionality of the Indiana Law in 2008.
The Republican authorities hastened to extend this practice to other states.
Over the last two years, they have promoted bills in 34 states that force voters to show a photo ID.
It is important to note that, unlike Quebec, US citizens do not have a universal identity card such as the health insurance card.
Indeed, 11% of US citizens, i.e. 21 million persons entitled to vote, do not have a photo ID issued by a government authority of their state.
In addition, five million new voters do not have such an ID in 2012.
However, more than a hundred dollars are often to be paid to obtain the required ID.
The new restrictions disproportionately affect young people, minorities and low-income people.
In fact, 25% of African-Americans, 15% of people with an income of less than $35,000, 18% of citizens over 65 years and 20% of voters between 18 and 29 years do not have the required photo ID.
This goes further.
Students who are seen as voters who vote more for democratic candidates are not allowed to use their photo ID issued by their institution in several states.
On the other hand, the same states allow members of fishing or hunting associations who choose more for the Republican side to use the cards issued by these associations for elections.
Before 2004, no federal state demanded proof of citizenship for voting.
Arizona was the first state to introduce such a demand.
Since 2011, a dozen states have passed laws calling for voters to demonstrate their US state citizenship.
These measures are clearly aimed at limiting Hispanic voices.
For it is obvious that two out of three Hispanic voters prefer the democratic party.
In addition, in 2011, Republican legislators promoted laws in eight states that abolished voters ’ registration on election day.
In addition, you have limited the right of individuals and groups to provide assistance to those voters who wish to register.
These restrictions are not without consequences.
For example, the campaign to register voters in the 2004 general elections helped to register about 10 million citizens.
The measures adopted since 2009 have reduced the proportion of new voters in 2010 by 17% compared to 2006.
In addition, Republican legislators have adopted laws in five other states aimed at shortening the period for early voting.
For example, in the 2008 Florida general election, 33% of the voters who voted in advance were Africans, even though they represent only 13% of federal voters.
The same applies to the Hispanic population.
The latter accounted for only 11% of voters, but 24% of the citizens who voted in advance.
By contrast, the whites, representing 76% of voters, accounted for only 46% of the voters who voted in advance.
Of course, democratic legislators and their supporters have vigorously opposed the adoption of laws restricting the registration of voters.
