The Higg's Boson analyses
The announcement of the probable discovery of the Higgs of Boson caused a sensation last summer, and for good reason.
In fact, it is believed that this boson is involved in nothing less than the mechanism responsible for the mass of all objects in the universe.
And finally it is the last particle whose existence was predicted by the standard model - our best or "least false" explanation of nature and the behaviour of matter - but not yet observed empirically.
But for physicists, it is not yet completely certain that this is really the Higgs.
We know, without the shadow of a doubt, that we have a real new particle, and that it is very similar to Higgs ’ s Boson, predicted by the standard model.
Moreover, this seems to be confirmed by new data presented this week at a major physics congress in Kyoto, but there is still a lack of data to be completely secure about it.
Nevertheless, let us assume that this is actually the Higgs, since there seems to be only a small risk of deceiving oneself, and let us look at what it is all about.
There is an inevitable indispensable law in this world, which means that two objects cannot be present simultaneously in the same place.
It is not possible to violate this rule - and try it not too strong as you will hurt.
For even if particle physics is a truly strange world, it turns out that such a law also applies to it: the Pauli exclusion principle, which states that two particles cannot occupy the same space at the same time, if they are in the same "quantum state", whereby this "state" generally consists of some of its properties.
Based on this, the physicists divide the particles into two categories.
In one corner there are the good citizens, who are called Fermione and obey the Pauli principle.
And in the other, the bosons move, an evil gang of anarchists, to whom nothing is sacred - in any case not this principle, which means that they can indeed be in the same place at the same time.
These bosons are divided into two groups according to the website The Particle Adventure of the Berkeley Laboratories (which is by the way absolutely amazing): the mesons, which we will not treat here and the "power-particles", through which the great forces of nature spread and with which the Higgs of Boson would somehow be related.
But it must be emphasized here that these bosons are not all as exotic creatures as one might think.
If you are able to read this chronicle, then only thanks to a boson of extraordinary banality: the photon or the "light particle", which is the "messenger" of the electromagnetic force.
When a particle accelerates with an electric charge or changes the direction, the electromagnetic field is "disturbed" exactly at this place, like a pebble that was thrown into a pond.
This "disturbance" creates an electromagnetic wave (light, infrared or ultraviolet radiation, etc.), and this wave is nothing but a photon and thus one of the bosons "carriers of force".
Stable field
The same is true for the Higgs and Boson, with the difference that another field, the Higgs and Field, must be "disturbed" so that this boson can be seen.
However, the Higgs Field is much more stable than the electromagnetic field; the pathogen must reach very high energies, a little comparable to a frozen pond whose surface could only be scattered by a very large rock.
Therefore a huge particle accelerator like the CERN is required - the Large Hadron Collider is a ring with a circumference of 27 km! - to achieve such energies.
The analogy with the electromagnetic field is again helpful to explain the relationship between the Higgs and the mass.
In fact, it is not all particles and not all materials that interact with the electromagnetic field.
Some, like magnets, do this, but others do not - for example, a sheet of paper would never keep itself in the fridge.
And equally, not all particles interact with the Higgs Field: those who do have a mass, while the others (like the photon) have no mass.
For what can all these research be 'good', Mrs Plamondon asks?
For science, they are used to verify the standard model (SM), and they also enable physicists to closely investigate all deviations between the observations and the predictions of the SM.
By the way, there are numerous physicists who eagerly hope that such deviations will be found, as the slightest difference could open a door to a "new physics" and plug some holes of the model.
It must be said that the latter still has great defects, since it does not provide an explanation for gravity (ups!) and dark matter, which forms about 80% of the matter of the universe (again ups!).
However, such deviations have not yet been found at CERN.
Impact
The impact of this research on the general population is more difficult to predict, but it would be wrong to assume that there is no.
By the way: in the early 1960s, the laser pioneers in the Bell Laboratories did not suspect that their work would trigger such a revolution.
They saw scientific applications, but nothing else.
In fact, the late physicist Willard Boyle - who worked in the Bell Labs, in which the laser was invented in the 1960s, and who himself developed the first permanent screed laser (the first ones were pulsed) in 1962 - has already said that the laser was rather regarded as a "laboratory play" at the beginning.
Imagine yourself...
Applications can also result from all the instruments that surround research.
For example, Willard Boyle developed a small light sensor in 1969 during his optics work.
Although it was not the original purpose, this sensor now serves all digital cameras worldwide as an "eye" and has brought it the Nobel Prize in Physics in 2009.
Of course, this does not mean that the activities of the LHC will inevitably change our lives, but it means that you can never really know...
Palliative care - the best way to die... | Le Devoir
Quebec recently discussed the sensitive issue of the end of life with its Committee on "Dignity".
The debate must be resumed shortly, although a draft law is being prepared.
However, much remains to be done in this important area.
Le Devoir has tried to look at this more closely.
A few weeks ago Mr. L. lived alone in his apartment in Montérégie.
The prostate cancer that consumed him had left him a period of two years.
"They gave me five years to live, I've managed seven years," he said half-heartedly, lying in his bed at the home of Palliative Care Victor Gadbois in Beloeil, where he had arrived the day before.
"However, it is always a shock, you cannot be prepared for it," he says.
The disease does its job: an immeasurable weakness prevents him from going to the toilet alone and even eating himself.
Sitting at the table before a delicious lunch, he resigned to let himself be helped with food.
Courageously he even succeeds in smiling and talking to the strangers who are busy around him, bringing him his medicine, and offering him a bath.
The courage of ordinary death.
"My greatest wish is to heal my diarrhea because it is humiliating," he says.
A few hours later, the team found a cure for this evil.
"In the course of our lives, we learn that a man is peeing standing," says Pierre Brodeur, a psychologist in the home of Victor Gadbois.
Returning to the childhood phase is unacceptable humiliation for certain people.
"This depends on the person's ability to take a step backwards," he notes.
In the opinion of several people who work in palliative care, great events take place in the midst of these regressions.
Patients who are sent to the home for palliative care Victor Gadbois all suffer from cancer.
They have a maximum life expectancy of three months.
At this stage, doctors and nurses who take care of them no longer heal them with so-called "healing" care.
For Mrs. A., 89 years, the worst fear is to die "consciously and by suffocation".
But through the illness I really got to know my children.
"I have good children," she adds.
"I have no more wishes in life," she says before she accepts that she is put on a mask to help her breathe.
In the next few days, she still expects a last visit of her son, who comes from Italy.
In the home of Victor Gadbois, a group of volunteers offer body care and food intake assistance.
Palliative care is used when there are no other possibilities.
To make dying more pleasant.
In Quebec comes to 11,700 inhabitants a bed for palliative care.
This is very little if one takes into account that one day we will all die.
Here life continues under the best possible conditions, explains Dr. Christiane Martel, one of the doctors of the home.
Both at the level of physical, emotional or spiritual comfort.
The dying person is given a mouth care with Brandy or Pepsi, depending on the wish.
Diabetics no longer have to control their blood sugar levels.
And death is part of everyday life.
Last night we served Mr. X a beer that died during the night.
This morning his son will drink the beer at the foot of the deceased.
"We help relatives and patients alike," reports Nursing Director Nathalie Savard.
In the home of Victor Gadbois is not a day like the other.
In addition to an old man of 93 years, who enjoys the last family meeting in the courtyard and is well supported by his pillows while one stumbles in his honor, a young man of 36 years, surrounded by his parents, his wife and his two young children, dies tragically after trying everything to survive.
"For six months, three to five beds have always been occupied with cancer patients under the age of 45," says Dr. Christiane Martel with concern.
53% of the patients assigned to the home Victor Gadbois come from their home, 47% from the hospital.
Problem of access to palliative care
It is said that 77% of Canadians do not have access to palliative care, i.e. care that is supposed to relieve the suffering of patients when the latter has reached the final stage of their lives, both at home, in the hospital or in a nursing home.
And several organizations, such as the home Victor Gadbois and the Society for Domestic Palliative Care in Greater Montreal, specialize more or less exclusively in the care of cancer patients.
It is precisely this great inadequacy in Quebec health care that ensures that several palliative doctors are concerned about adopting a law regulating euthanasia and assisted suicide.
Since the month of October, a manifesto has been circulating, signed by prominent personalities of palliative care such as Dr. Balfour Mount and Dr. Bernard Lapointe, to express their contradiction to such an initiative.
According to Dr. Christiane Martel, Quebec ’ s healthcare system is inefficient enough to ensure that all have the right to high-quality palliative care before being accepted for euthanasia.
Recently, she says, I saw a patient who was 14 days in distress with great pain, without taking any measures to alleviate her.
I fear that patients only want to die because they do not receive adequate health care.
At the same time, several oncologists treat their patients, despite the worst predictions, until the last day.
The chances of survival of Hélène Richard were already minimal when she broke down a burdensome chemotherapy.
When I told my oncologist that I would cancel the treatment, she answered me that she regretted that I was abandoning the fight, she told me.
However, she had told me that I was in the end!
No omnipotent care
Dr. Martel believes that 90% of patients who have asked to die are grateful to the nursing staff for not accepting this wish after their pain has been relieved by a team of palliative care.
It must be made clear, however, that palliative care is not omnipotent in pain treatment.
According to Elsie Monereau, head of palliative care at the Montreal Domestic Palliative Care Society, 8% of patients do not respond to pain treatment.
At the very end of life, physicians often fall back on the terminal sedation, which amounts to either falling asleep sporadically or permanently until the time of his death.
We can no longer pretend to see this side of suffering.
Patients without pain relief will increasingly have the opportunity to resort to this terminal sedation.
Patients whose pain is not relieved all say the same sentence: "I want to die."
But that does not necessarily mean "I want you to fall asleep", but "I want my pain to be relieved".
