With Bitcoin payment and selling is possible without bank
The opposite of the current monetary exchange on the basis of central banks, identified transactions and handling fees between stakeholders.
Moreover, as so often happens in these technologies, a political vision is tangible: the conviction that the current monetary system, shaped by bank monopolies, leads to financial crises.
In fact, the Bitcoin invented by Satoshi Nakamoto (a pseudonym) is both a virtual currency (but convertible into dollars, euros, etc.) and a protocol for secure exchange such as BitTorrent, which allows direct exchange of files.
Some 200,000 transactions have already been recorded with 15,000 computers in the network.
Some thousand websites accept Bitcoin as a donation or as a means of payment.
After reaching a peak of $30 (€23) in June 2011, Bitcoin ’ s rate fell to $2 five months later before recovering to around $10 (the rates are listed on the bitcoincharts.com website).
Nothing particularly impressive compared to world trade in real currencies or financial products.
Nevertheless, the European Central Bank (ECB) has shown interest in this in a report on virtual currencies published in October.
She describes Bitcoin as "the virtual currency with the greatest success", "in competition with the dollar or euro" and "similar to conventional currencies".
Bitcoin differs from other types of virtual currencies, such as the "credits" used to advance in a video game that you can win or buy (and sometimes exchange) through games.
The social network Facebook has also developed such a system.
However, each time trade is controlled and processed by a central authority.
With Bitcoin, all network nodes are simultaneously depositors of the invoice book, auditors, money issuers as well as buyers and sellers.
How does this network work?
Each transaction between two users actually takes place between two E-mail addresses in the form of an E-mail.
With the difference that the user can choose a different address for each payment, which ensures anonymity.
A number of data related to this transaction is electronically signed by a double encryption system.
In this way, the network can check the authenticity of the transaction.
Using the contents of the file, it is also possible to ensure that the Bitcoins traded are present in the public accounts accounting book distributed throughout the network.
The decisive step is to include this new transaction in this book.
This is done through a mathematical task launched on the computers, with the winner, who is a kind of temporary central banker, having the privilege of adding this additional line.
It is a fragmentation of the file, i.e. the conversion of a large file into a shorter and unique electronic fingerprint.
The computers "take" the new transaction and add a number to it before the whole thing is "chopped".
The goal is to find the number that gives a special fingerprint (many zeros at the beginning).
If this number has been found, the other nodes can effortlessly check if it is the right one.
The transaction is thus permanently linked to the chain of all other transactions, and any modification would change the fingerprint.
If a user wants to pay the same money twice very quickly (less than 10 minutes) for fraud, only one of the two transactions would be validated by the network and the other remains unconnected, as both have different fingerprints.
The computer that solved the task receives 50 Bitcoins.
To prevent inflation, this reward is halved regularly, probably before the end of 2012.
The Bitcoins in circulation are thus limited to 21 million, but can be divided up to one hundredmillionth, which leaves a certain margin...
In addition, the difficulty of the task is increased with every improvement of the computing power.
The life of the network has already had ups and downs.
The websites that provide Bitcoin services were attacked and Bitcoin deposits stolen.
"The vulnerability does not affect the actual protocol," says Pierre Noizat, who has just introduced Paymium, which is a real money payment company using the Bitcoin network.
The ECB also reports on the possibilities of money laundering through this anonymous service.
However, cash also has these shortcomings.
Important actors such as Wikipedia refuse donations of this kind.
They are accepted by others like the WordPress blog platform.
Recently, Adi Shamir and Dorit Ron from the Weizmann Institute in Israel analyzed the accounting book and showed that almost 80% of Bitcoins are not in circulation.
A "Mega Final Sale" was launched in November.
"Thirty thousand dollars have been exchanged," said Jon Holmquist, who works for the company Coinabul, who converted Bitcoins into gold.
Pierre Noizat, who is also the author of a book on this currency, firmly believes in the potential of this technology as a transactional network.
His system Paytunia corresponds to a credit card (with real money) or contactless payment with a mobile phone, but uses Bitcoin to validate transactions that are cheaper.
In addition, the owner manages his identity and can thus remain anonymous.
The system can be easily implemented by dealers, and the latter do not need to install new terminals or computer programs.
You simply have to specify an address that can be "photographed and recognized" by a phone, says Pierre Noizat, who assures that he has thousands of users.
There is a general trend in which hierarchical systems are being reconsidered in favour of more horizontal systems.
"It will take some time for Bitcoin to prevail, but 2013 could be a turning point," he predicts.
The ECB, by the way, provides in its report to reassess the various risks, which are now highly regarded, in the event of a success of this currency.
