A constitution with the crusher rod in Egypt
This is a new poker game by President Mohammed Morsi.
While Egypt remains divided more than ever in relation to the Constitutional Declaration, which temporarily grants it unlimited power, it has decided to put everything on one card.
To the surprise of all, he announced on Wednesday that the Constituent Assembly would adopt its final version the next day.
Just one week ago, the Head of State granted this plenary two additional months to complete its work.
Egypt has now relied for almost two years on a provisional text that has been amended several times, weakening institutional stability and leading to legal confusion.
This new initiative has only caused the country to become even more divided.
For his opponents, the President persists in his "autocratic delirium" by continuing to "break his word" and "trample the law".
On the side of its supporters, it is assured that it is a way to end the institutional and political crisis as quickly as possible and to accelerate the transition process.
A referendum should be held within 14 days.
A very short period, which forces the brothers to renounce their intention to explain the text to the Egyptians section by section.
For the President, it is also a way to rediscover his public and democratic legitimacy while the protest is raging throughout the country.
After confirming in an interview with the American weekly Time, Mohammed Morsi seems convinced that the Egyptians will vote benevolently.
In view of the fact that an ultimatum is being put to the Egyptian people with this resorting to a hasty vote: "Either it agrees with my draft or I reserve the unlimited authority", the latter should supposedly put an end to it after the adoption of the Constitution.
85 mostly Islamist members of this Constituent Assembly adopted the text yesterday in a strange atmosphere.
The majority of Liberals have not responded to the call.
Shortly before the Constitutional Declaration in mid-November, they turned away because they felt that they were unable to bring their views to bear.
Representatives of human rights organisations, religious minorities or civil society have acted equally.
To achieve quorum, 11 people, deputy members, were added in a hurry yesterday morning.
Some are very close to the Muslim Brotherhood.
It is not surprising that the articles were mostly adopted unanimously.
By the way, the commentators found it entertaining that the only difference of opinion of the day... was expressed at the time of prayer, since some members of the body felt that the clock of the Constituent Assembly did not go exactly.
The text, which was adopted last night, consists of 234 articles.
Finally, Article 2, which drew all attention, remains identical to that of the 1971 Constitution and states that "the principles of Sharia are the main source of law".
The Salafist parties, for which the establishment of Islamic law is an important demand, had the hope of replacing "the principles" with "the rules", which would have made a stricter application possible.
For the Islamists, the fact that this article has not been changed is proof of their good will and respect for the other members of Egyptian society.
"hypocrisy" reciprocates the liberals who regard this only as propaganda.
According to them, the Islamization of the Constitution takes place through other articles.
In particular, they have Article 220 in mind, which recognises an advisory role for the University of Al-Azhar, in particular with regard to the review of conformity with the laws of Sharia law.
According to the Egyptian specialist Sophie Pommier, this is disturbing, because "the people who are called for an opinion have not been elected and have no democratic legitimacy.
One can see here the first signs of a theocracy. "
Liberals ’ fears are also fueled by the fact that the next rector of this university should be far less moderate than the current one.
"There is currently no concrete religious commitment.
With this Constitution we remain within the framework of the bourgeois state.
Most lawyers who have worked on this text are not Ulema, but academics who have been trained in part in the French system, "summarizes Alexis Blouet, who writes a doctoral thesis on the Egyptian constitutional transition.
However, he acknowledges that "there may be ambiguity in relation to Article 220, since the terms used are borrowed from the religious vocabulary.
One refers here in particular to the "Fiqh" [Islamic jurisprudence].
And in the future, the question could be raised as to how far civil judges are competent to decide. "
In addition to its religious aspect, the text adopted yesterday is strongly criticised for the far-reaching powers it grants the President of the Republic.
The Muslim Brotherhood argues that they are significantly reduced compared to the former regime.
Another point of contention: the powers of the army.
In accordance with the wishes of the military, the examination of the defence budget is not submitted to Parliament but to a national defence council.
Similarly, there will be no ban on civil proceedings in military courts, as called for by the associations for the defence of human rights.
The latter also share their fears about the text they regard as threatening liberty.
The fact of blasphemy is maintained and insults are now banned, which could have serious consequences for the right to freedom of expression, especially for the press.
Furthermore, no article relates to the protection of women, underlines Heba Morayef of Human Rights Watch.
In your opinion, the only positive point is the prohibition of torture by Article 36.
This word was not contained in the previous Constitution.
While the Egyptian president had to speak on television last night, demonstrations are planned for this afternoon.
The proponents of the head of state will march up Saturday.
In Israel Ukrainian tourists expect sacred sites, the navel of the world and a sea of brine
The Promised Land unites in itself the glory of biblical truths, modern comfort and untouched nature.
AIF gives you the five main reasons for a visit to Israel.
Bow in front of the holy places
Visit the river Jordan, where Jesus was baptized.
It is said that all who bathe in this river receive God's blessing.
Galilee is the place where Jesus performed his miracles: the conversion of water into wine on a wedding celebration, walking on the water, the confinement of the sea tower and fishing.
Just here Jesus appeared to his disciples after the resurrection.
Most of the sanctuaries are located in Jerusalem.
Here believers walk the Passion or Way of the Cross of Jesus Christ (in Latin: Via Dolorosa).
The path starts at the Roman fortress Antonia, Pretorium, where the court was, and leads through the streets of the old town to the grave church on Mount Golgotha, where there is the crucifixion, the anointing stone and the tomb of Jesus.
This is the Christian view of the navel of the world, which symbolises the salvation of humanity.
The convent of the Holy Cross in Jerusalem stands at the place where, according to a Christian legend, the tree from which the cross was made for the crucifixion of Jesus grew.
In Jerusalem there is also the most sacred place of the Jews - the Wailing Wall, the remains of a temple destroyed by the Romans in 70 AD.
Traditionally, people of different faiths leave notes with wishes, which are then fulfilled.
Journey to the heights
The ruins of the Massada fortress form the remains of the secret hiding place before enemies that Herod the Great had built for his family in the year 25 AD.
They are situated on a rock wall in the mountains at 450 meters above sea level.
Only mountaineers can reach the ruins by themselves.
All the others bring a cable car to this historic summit.
In the north of the country in 1600 to 2040 meters height is the famous ski resort Hermon, in which it attracts countless tourists in the winter months.
There is a shuttle bus from the foot of the mountain.
The ski slopes have a total length of 45 kilometres.
According to an ancient legend, pagan gods lived on the top of the mountain.
Visit unique museums
There are almost 300 museums in this country.
With only one trip not all of them can be visited.
But at least the five most interesting of them should be paid a visit.
Among them is the Israel museum near the Knesset (Parliament).
Old Qumran manuscripts or scrolls of the Dead Sea, found in rock caves in the Judean desert, and about 500 thousand archaeological and anthropological exhibits are kept there.
The Museum of Art in Tel Aviv is also worth a visit.
The collection of works by the Impressionists and Expressionists Monet, Pissaro, Renoir, Cézanne, Sisley, Matisse, Modigliani, Chagall and Picasso is exhibited there.
In Akko you can visit the museum in the Bad Al Basha, which houses several halls of ancient Turkish baths with sculptures of the then visitors and bathers.
In Caesarea you should visit the unique private Ralli Museum, where you can admire Dali and Rodin sculptures.
There are neither museum guides nor souvenir shops.
Admission is free and donations are rejected.
The fifth museum, namely the Holocaust and Yad Vashem in Tel Aviv, tells of one of the most shocking chapters in history.
The most touching section is the monument to the children, built in memory of the 1.5 million children who were destroyed in the concentration camps and gas chambers.
When entering the room there is complete darkness.
Stars sparkle.
And the names of the Jewish children and the countries in which they died resound.
Ukraine is also mentioned there.
Do something for health
The three main recreational areas of Israel lie on the shores of the Mediterranean Sea, the Red Sea and the Dead Sea.
In each of the three places there are swimming pools, water parks, dolphins and oceanariums.
Surprisingly, the Red Sea is also bathed in the winter months, as the water temperature does not fall below 21 ° C and the air warms up to 23 ° C.
The Dead Sea is even warmer and bathed all year round.
By the way, this unusual sea with a position of 417 meters below sea level is the deepest sea in the world.
Its turquoise blue water has a high salt content and thus carries even non-swimmers easily on the surface.
The surrounding landscape is indescribably beautiful.
Visitors come here for treatments using salt water (natural salt brine) and healing mud as well as for the treatment of skin inflammation, allergies, asthma, eczema, arthritis, bronchitis, diabetes and calming stressed nerves.
Touching the Mysteries of Antiquity
These secrets hold the old town of Tel Aviv, the city of Jaffa on the Mediterranean coast.
The famous sea route connecting Egypt, Syria, Anatolia and Mesopotamia ran through this city.
The city is mentioned in ancient Greek and ancient Egyptian legends.
According to tradition Noah built his ark here, and Perseus saved the beautiful Andromeda, with which he lived a long and happy life in this place.
Tourists like to stroll through the narrow streets named after zodiac signs.
Fortuna is said to be the legend of all those who touch the walls in the alley with their zodiac sign.
In Jaffa you can meet newlyweds from all over Israel and even other countries at photo mines.
In Caesarea, the city of King Herod, you can stroll through the Roman theatre and conquer the fortress of the Crusaders.
In Roman times Caesarea was the most important city of Judea and residence of the Roman governors, including Pontius Pilate.
Nowadays evening concerts and operas are performed in the carefully restored theatre.
Booklist for tourists
If you go to Israel, don ’ t worry about your bad English skills: about 30% of Israelis speak Russian.
The money in the trip is rather not taken in euros, but in dollars, which can simply be changed into shekels (current exchange rate: 1 dollar to 3.8 shekels).
In the city you can mostly take the bus, but in Jerusalem there is also an expressway and in Haifa the only subway line of the country with six stations connecting the lower city with the upper city.
In fact, it is an underground funicular.
A trip within the city costs 6 shekels regardless of the means of transport, which includes a transfer for a journey of up to 1.5 hours.
According to Jewish tradition, the Sabbath is celebrated in Israel on Saturdays.
From Friday evening until sunset on Saturday, markets and shops are closed and public transport rests.
And on Sunday morning the working week begins.
In many cafes, restaurants and restaurants only kosher food is served, which excludes pork, sea products, fish without sheds and dishes that contain both milk and meat products.
Instead, you can choose between different dishes with mutton and beef, soups and desserts (prepared with coconut milk), traditional Jewish humus paste, various sauces, fried balls of pureed beans and peas (falafel) as well as fruits and vegetables.
There are no stray dogs in the streets of Israeli cities.
But there are many well-fed cats that stroll through the streets comfortably and undisturbed.
In the evening you can even see them sleeping on the roofs of parking cars.
The cats like animated places and do not say no to treats.
A rental car costs between 37 dollars per day (Hyundai Getz) and 188 dollars (Audi A6, Volvo S80) depending on the brand.
The insurance costs an additional 15 dollars per day.
And bike rental costs 15 shekels per day.
Tickets for museums cost 30 shekels on average.
In figures
In 2012, more than three million tourists from all over the world visited Israel.
Most adventurers and recreational seekers came from Russia, France, Germany, Italy, England, the USA and Ukraine.
From January to October 2012, 118.8 thousand Ukrainian tourists came to the Promised Country, an increase of 51% compared to the same period in 2010, before the visa requirement was lifted on 9 February 2011.
"The great and powerful" leads to Moscow: Migrants save money for language
While MEPs and civil rights activists discuss the benefits of the law on binding language tests for migrants, criminals are already acting with counterfeit certificates
Every year 13 million guest workers come to Moscow, Saint Petersburg and other cities in Russia.
Most of them are the citizens of Central Asia: Uzbekistan, Tajikistan and Turkmenistan.
Their only goal is to earn money for the maintenance of the families who remain in their homeland.
On 1 December, a law entered into force requiring each migrant to take a test certifying knowledge of the Russian language.
Until now, this scheme only applies to migrants who want to work in the services sector, in the municipal housing sector and in the retail sector.
However, according to the Federal Migration Authority, tests should become mandatory in future for all guest workers.
Not only language tests, but also tests must be put into Russian history and the foundations of legislation.
Language skills must be proven both for obtaining and extending the work permit.
Exceptions apply only to citizens of countries where Russian is the official language.
Also excluded from this law are persons who received their certificates of education and diplomas before the disintegration of the USSR in 1991.
Sense, problem and protection of rights
The whole of the exams will be held under the aegis of the Pushkin Institute for Russian Language, the Russian University of International Friendship, the Moscow State University, St. Petersburg State University and other Russian universities.
Migrants can pass the tests in all cities and already more than 160 centres have been opened in Russia.
The initiative to introduce the tests was supported by Members of the State Duma and the Federal Migration Authority.
Citizens' rights activists, on the other hand, asked several times before the law came into force in the press: what does it actually bring about?
What changes does the requirement to have language skills bring, both for the Russians and for the guest workers?
Above all, the spokesman for the Migration Authority said, it was about reducing the number of forced laborers.
"Many are now talking about the protection of the rights of migrant workers," said Viktor Zebelev, head of the Representation of the Federal Migration Authority in Tajikistan.
Their rights must, however, be protected from their departure.
Only an organized recruitment will solve 90% of the problems of foreign workers.
Problems are encountered by migrants without a job, education, language skills and medical evaluation.
Sebelev is convinced that a future migrant without language skills will inevitably encounter people with evil intentions who, on the pretext of help, will put him in a dark, narrow barrack, where he will endure with dozens of his equal months without food and documents and work 12 to 14 hours a day.
We receive many complaints from our migrants.
"In the home you are promised the one, and on arrival you will be cheated, get their passports taken off and will not receive the promised wage," confirms the head of the Head of Labour Migration of the Tajik Migration Authority, Tolib Schwaripov.
Not scolding, boss!
Nevertheless, many citizens of the Central Asian republics who want to earn their money in Russia admit that they cannot only speak the language of the target country, but can hardly express themselves in writing in their own language.
Of course, this is not so much their fault as the evil: only a few Turkmen, Uzbeks and Tajiks can afford a reasonable basic education.
Because in their families there is not even money to feed the children, let alone to buy them decent clothes, shoes and school clothes.
As teenagers, these children immediately seize the first opportunity to earn money.
"It is difficult without language skills," they admit.
"You feel humiliated and inferior."
Civil rights activists stress the following important aspect of the law.
Only migrants with legal status must take the test.
If you do not have this status, there is no examination and therefore no official work.
Meanwhile, most of the guest workers remain illegally in Russia.
"Welcome" or "Forbidden access for unauthorised persons"
Many migrants confirm that it is not easy to obtain official status in Russia.
The reason is bureaucratic hurdles and, of course, the linguistic difficulties.
In addition, the legalization costs money: 12 to 16 thousand rubles.
Fake registration can be done quickly and only for one and a half thousand.
The staff of the Russian police know that our documents are mostly fake and we are not registered, and then there are cases of blackmail.
"They want one or two hundred rubles for cigarettes and tea," says Tajike Umed Huskadamov to journalists.
"Do not shy away from costs for false papers"
Already on the day the law entered into force, it turned out that not only the registration documents of migrants can be falsified.
Some counterfeit certificates certifying the completion of the language test have already been confiscated by employees of the Federal Migration Authority.
The counterfeit papers were printed with an ordinary color printer.
Of course, the new owners did not get this for nothing: every migrant who hoped to save himself so the tests paid for the document seven thousand rubles.
This is more than twice as much as the cost of the official test: it costs a migrant worker three thousand rubles.
The most important immediate task is to protect the system from corruption, so that the certificates cannot be bought easily, both officials and civil rights activists are in agreement.
For the moment, the authorities can only promise to give guest workers who will fall through the test for the first time that they will have time for a basic language course.
In addition, new arrivals without language skills are offered positions in areas where no active communication with people is necessary.
Ministry of the Interior ignores illegal arms market
Proportion of legal weapons in criminal offences extremely low
The Russian Ministry of the Interior is planning to tighten the arms law for private arms owners.
The authorities are responding to recent events: injured in shootings on weddings and seven dead in the shooting of Moscow lawyer Dmitry Verogradov.
The police want to ban the use of non-lethal weapons in public and to raise the age of possession of firearms from 18 to 21 years.
The proposal was supported by Irina Jarowaja, Chairman of the Duma Committee on Security and Corruption, and promised that the amendments to the Arms Act will soon be submitted to the Duma.
Not everyone is satisfied that the Russian authorities want to combat the problems by "attracting the screws".
An open letter has been published on the Internet, the author - representatives of various arms associations - calling on the authorities to refrain from "meaningless tightening up".
The percentage of crimes with registered weapons is very low, said the criminal lawyer, Vasily Lesnikov, the Russian service of the BBC.
According to the Interior Ministry statistics, 142 crimes involving the use of registered weapons were committed in 2012 over six months, while a total of 1.168 thousand crimes were committed for the same period.
The authors of the open letter are convinced that tightening up the law for private arms owners will not prevent criminals from using themselves on the black market.
According to the authors, at present any weapon can be found in Moscow for little money.
Meanwhile, the Ministry of the Interior stresses that the proliferation of illegal weapons is under control.
Suppliers: from factories to officers
The weapons enter the black market via several channels.
There are five such main channels, told a former colonel Viktor Baranez, who worked for ten years in the Ministry of Education and the General Staff.
Screenshot of a website that accepts arms orders
The first channel is the army or military, i.e. weapons stolen during the fighting in the Caucasus.
"The weapons were stolen both by the Russian officers and the Caucasians themselves," says Baranets.
On the second channel come illegal weapons that are stolen from criminals.
Baranez explains that this includes weapons stolen both from the police ’ s weapons chambers and directly from law enforcement staff.
Other illegally sold weapons come from military weapons camps.
Explosions often occurred in many military camps.
"There is evidence that some cases were arson, to cover up the lack of weapons," says the former military member.
According to Baranez, arms manufacturers also contribute to the black market.
"Nowadays, there are countless private arms factories that do not stand up to international competition and therefore slash the weapons under the hand of the black market, for example in Moscow," the expert reports.
Another channel of the black market is smuggling.
Especially many guns and rifles come from poor countries like Kyrgyzstan.
"There is an own, sometimes artisanal production there as well as a mafia, which organizes the smuggling", explains the former military member.
Where do the weapons come from?
Experts calculated the proportion of each of the five channels involved in supplying illegal weapons to the black market.
In 2011, a report was written by the Centre for Problem Analysis and State Administration.
The experts analysed reports from the Ministry of the Interior and the Federal Service for State Statistics, Criminal Literature and publicly available data on weapons portals.
According to the investigators, most of the illegal weapons come from the army and legal protection authorities.
Half of all the weapons on the black market are there because of the 'guilt of those responsible who have come to deal with weapons in their work', the report says.
According to the researchers, 17% of the weapons come from conflict zones, 14% go back to theft in arms production, and 5% come from illegal excavations.
A sales advisor for an arms store that does not want to be named, assures that weapons that are found in illegal excavations have not been bought for a long time since they are outdated.
According to him, it is more common for traders to obtain supplies in a weapons camp.
A weapon, for example a gun of type TT, is purchased via a ensign.
The weapon is issued and passed through the fence.
"The dealer brings the weapon to the city and sells it there for 900 euros per piece with two magazines," he says.
"The police, of course, are aware of everything and therefore, if they cannot comply with the plan to detect crimes, periodically carry out inspection purchases at dealers offering illegal weapons," adds the sales advisor.
"Like in a luxury shop"
Buyers and sellers find each other most frequently through acquaintances.
I had looked at websites and blogs when someone became aware of me and suggested that I come to the station "Begowaja", where a person would wait for me to bring me to a certain place where we could negotiate the price.
I only learned the price of the weapon there
Military Commentator Viktor Baranez
"To get a weapon, I need a friend who has contacts," says the sales consultant. "I have such a friend, but I don't trust him."
There are traders in the markets, but there you have to go and agree with a code like "Ivan Ivanovich, who lets align that the daughter has lost a tooth".
I am even coming to some drums about a friend to whom I trust.
He also delivers the rings to me only because he knows that I do not whistle him.
Newcomers are looking for weapons in different ways.
Former military member Viktor Baranez tried to buy illegal weapons in the mid-1990s when he wrote an article on this subject.
According to him, the schemes have not changed.
He got a photo album in which "everything possible" was shown.
"I felt like in the luxury shop," the military member remembers.
According to Baranez, the buyer does not get the cat in the bag, but can try everything.
As a potential customer, I do not just buy, but drive with the seller into the forest, and there we set up a target.
"I can then shoot there, and if I am convinced that the weapon has a good shot, we negotiate with each other," the expert describes the procedure.
Shopping from the sofa
