"The brain can only be moderately overlittered"
The topic of enlarged reality, which is popular with fans of modern technologies, is usually perceived by the lens of special glasses lately.
First, Google presented a working model at its annual conference in the summer, and in November it became known that Microsoft had also applied for a patent.
In conversation with the head of the group for interactive 3D technologies in the Microsoft laboratory in Cambridge Shahram Izadi, it becomes clear that the glasses were only a transit station for the company ’ s scientists.
It stimulates the possibility of manipulating virtual objects in the air with bare hands and creating virtual open spaces.
- Please describe briefly which research your group is conducting.
- We deal with the interaction of man and machine, but want to expand the limits of this interaction.
So far, most of humanity has remained stuck in the phase of working with pixels on flat screens, which are sometimes touched.
However, we want to look ahead for 5 to 10 years and foresee the radical changes in this interaction.
For example, the Xbox console and the Kinect sensors are a step forward, and nowadays no Xbox is sold without Kinect, as everyone is interested in motion control.
- What is waiting for us in the future?
- Although Kinect has brought the interaction to a physical level, much still happens on the flat screen, sometimes in 3D.
The input of information (the system receives more data) could be improved, the output has not yet been decisive.
We try to change this, work on real three-dimensional display systems based on various technologies, including projections.
We need to release the computer world into our physical world and make it more tangible.
However, it is necessary that not only the user but also his environment is recognized.
Then we could add virtual objects to the real world much easier.
And first and foremost we should get rid of these ravaged Virtual and Reality helmets!
- What do you think about voice control?
It is popular, but is it not overvalued?
- It is certainly not the all-purpose solution, as it raises questions about privacy, because one does not always want to inform all those around about his actions and intentions.
Actually, any kind of interaction with computers is good, but each in its particular niche.
For example, in the area of controlling objects in public places, we worked on a project in which we experimented with short and short gestures instead of spreading.
The gestures were not recorded by the object camera, but by a bracelet that registered the movements of the bones and muscles.
It is still relatively large, but could theoretically be reduced to the size of a wristwatch.
But overall, the future belongs to mixed types of control, such as gestures and language.
- How?
- We would ask you, for example, to give you this jacuzzi can?
They say it and at the same time point to it.
- Normally I just say it.
- Oh, it would be very difficult to see.
- Does that mean you want the user to adapt to what a machine can afford at the respective time and what not?
- Not necessarily, but this is about a mutual approach.
I think that in the near future we will have to work in particular on the development of new sensor types, which will enable people to understand reactions more precisely.
These can be laser sensors, for example, as they offer good resolution in depth, which is very important.
- What requirements do you place on modern cameras based on your work with the Xbox Kinect sensors?
Is there a lack of resolution, depth or something else?
- The present generation is basically a good starting point for our work in the field of three-dimensional recognition.
Of course, 8 megapixels at a speed of 1000 fps would not be bad.
But the main thing is not the megapixels themselves, but the quality of the matrix and the depth.
From this point of view, all current technologies are not good enough for us, as the developers of the algorithms have more work.
It must be taken into account not only the resolution along the X and Y axes, but also along the Z axis.
The speed and number of images per second are also important.
The movements of the human being are extremely dynamic and frankly said, the current 30 fps are too little especially for gestures.
Stephen Betishes developed in our laboratory in Redmond a contact sensor with a adjustable processing delay between 1 and 100 milliseconds, whereby today's commercial sensors are closer to the second value (60 to 100).
Not everyone understands how much this affects the interaction between man and machine.
For my work I needed exactly such a device, only without touch control and with more pictures per second.
- Should the number of cameras not be increased?
- Kinect currently works with three "cameras", one of which is actually an infrared transmitter and the other a receiver for the reflected signal.
And the third camera is actually an ordinary RGB camera.
It does not serve to calculate the object depth.
More cameras could possibly solve the problem...
Or strengthen the problem, as more calculations would be necessary.
It would be nice to have a flexible Kinect system similar to that in which we could play with different camera inclinations to determine how this helps us in the three-dimensional determination of a position.
- If I remember correctly, Microsoft unlike Google did not present its glasses to the public.
Do you not think that glasses have the best prospects in terms of applying the technology of expanded reality in everyday life?
- Of course it is not pleasant to always hold a smartphone in the raised hand while on the road, but I think the following: The greatest variant would be a "changing" extended reality, in which we could switch from the glasses to the smartphone via a cloud,
The glasses are a personal gadget and it is their strength (only you can see private items), but also their weakness, because an extended reality by means of glasses prevents you from working on virtual objects together with others.
- Imagine for a moment that the manipulation of virtual holograms in the air is accessible not only to Tony Stark from Iron Man, but also to normal mortals.
There is a problem that critics of this idea often point to: there is no tangible reaction!
The hands feel nothing at all!
What answers does your group want to give to this objection?
- In my lectures I often speak of the fact that the expanded reality is the seventh breakthrough in the interaction between man and machine.
I think the eighth breakthrough could well be the integration of tactile perception.
An interesting method is currently using the second hand as a somewhat unusual projection pad.
She perceives pressure excellently!
But there are also technologies that are actually geared towards giving the "pictures in the air" something manual, for example, the interference of some directed ultrasonic rays at a certain point where the finger is, creates a feeling that is at the moment still as weak as someone bloated over the palms.
There are also bands for the wrist that affect the nerve endings in the fingers, also that is a potential direction.
- Have you tried to outwit the brain?
Let it think that it feels what it should feel if it just sees something?
- This is a good idea, so we have not tried yet.
Here lies another task, with which we will have to fight for a long time, namely to let a person physically in a closed room believe, he is instead in an open, practically infinite space; here we work on concepts with treadmills (other than in fitness studios), mobile platforms as well as large balls.
So far, the brain can only be moderately overlittered, and there are still many busy years ahead of us.
This is precisely what makes the work in the field of virtual reality so attractive for a researcher: on many topics, we are only at the beginning.
