Birth in space
Earth in danger.
Global warming or collision with killer asteroid.
Caravans of spaceships with strawberries on board are looking for a replacement planet.
In order to save humanity, the important question is how we can reproduce ourselves in weightlessness or on the replacement planet?
I do not think there are many choices.
In fact, there are only two real planets that we could at least hypothetically inhabit.
"Namely Mars and Venus," says the scientific assistant of the Astronomical Sternberg Institute Vladimir Surdin.
However, while the conditions on Mars are comparatively life-friendly, there is a temperature of 500 degrees on the surface of Venus.
Life would only be possible at high altitude or in the orbit of Venus, i.e. in space.
The researchers initially addressed the question of reproduction in space with regard to the flora.
Already half a century before, experiments with plants were carried out.
The fourth generation of peas bred in orbit did not differ in the slightest from earthly species.
It followed the breeding of insects, more precisely tiny fruit flies (Drosophila), in orbit.
In 1979, quail eggs were sent into space to explore how weightlessness affects the development of embryos.
It develops a normal chick.
But then the problem begins.
"The problem is that the chick must find support; it must be able to stand on his legs and start moving," explains Vladimir Sychev, head of the laboratory of the Institute for Medical Biological Problems RAN.
Without solid substrates the chicks surfaced wildly.
Ten hours later, the instincts of the newborn were completely blurred.
The chicks did not react to light and sounds.
Four days later they simply died.
"Twice we let chicks slip and then put it in, because it is simply impossible to work there with them," Vladimir Sychev notes on the failed experiment with chicks in space.
The last breeding cage with animals flew into orbit 16 years ago.
The experiments will continue in spring 2013.
However, only same-sex species will be found on the biosatellite "Bion".
There was an experiment with rats that were already fertilized into space.
In principle, nothing special was found.
"This was just with the biosatellites, but again it was only a single experiment, and the research must be continued," notes Vladimir Sychev.
After landing, the space rats got offspring.
The problem of reproduction directly in space has not yet been solved.
The task is difficult.
Animals that are torn out of their natural habitat simply cannot follow their reproductive instinct.
In contrast to animals, man could do that in principle.
The Homo sapiens is capable of abstract thinking and can create a similar emotional background.
Such experiments are not carried out from ethical considerations.
But women have been flying into space for 50 years.
There was the greatest risk at Tereshkova.
The most valuable that mankind possesses is the female organism.
Our seagull flew away, and no one on earth could have answered the following question: Does it survive space flight?
Will she be able to give birth to a child after this flight?
"After all, nobody answered this question," says space veteran Wachtang Watschnadse.
In June 1964, just one year after her space flight, the first female cosmonaut, Valentina Tereshkova, gave birth to a daughter.
The father of the child, Andriyan Nikolayev, was also cosmonaut.
In 1988, the second woman in space, Svetlana Savitskaya, who was orbit twice and even did work outside the space vehicle, gave birth to a son.
Nevertheless, a risk remains.
We only have very few cosmonauts, where everything went well after long flights and they got healthy offspring.
"The more, the more dangerous it is even on flights to the orbit," concludes cosmonaut Valery Polyakov, Hero of the Soviet Union and Hero of the Russian Federation.
Yet humanity must look for new ways in biotechnology, radiation protection, and the creation of artificial gravity.
The hydrolaboratory in the cosmonauts preparatory centre is a mandatory station during flight preparation.
Here in a suspended state the cosmonauts gain routine for the work in open space.
The water represents weightlessness.
Even if adults feel that water is pleasant, it is a foreign environment, but infants feel that water is a natural element.
It is as if the small Ichtyander bear witness to the fact that life on the land descended from the ocean.
There is a connection between the fact that a child is about 9 months in the mother ’ s stomach in the amniotic fluid, and that it can then become more easily accustomed to water.
In principle, this is logical, since from birth to first swimming only 2 weeks pass.
"This is too little time to forget," says baby swimming teacher Marina Aksenova.
Whereas weightlessness is a much more natural condition for a newborn child, the woman is not without gravity.
In the state of weightlessness, the abdominal and pelvic muscles reproduce enormously quickly and thus also the ability to squeeze out the child decreases.
Well, we bypass the pre-birth aid.
For example, the birth could also take place in a special chamber to squeeze out the child.
"But what happens then?" is the not insignificant question of Valery Polyakov.
On the other hand, the child also needs artificial gravity.
Without feeling the attraction of the earth, the organism cannot form the skeleton and muscles.
A newborn child cannot be put in an orbit like an adult for training.
He will simply lack what is of fundamental importance for his life.
"This experiment, which we carry out together, namely the birth of a child in a foreign environment, will lead to the birth of a disabled person, a completely unadapted person," says the head of the Bioethics Commission of the Institute for Medical Biological Problems RAN, Igor Pestow.
So far, the birth of children in space is mere theory.
At some point, however, it becomes a reality when the inhabitants of the Earth set out on a distant planet in their spaceships, which becomes the home for their offspring born in space.
NKU Chief: Control of the Black System Failed by Debt of Politics
In connection with public procurement, the Czech Republic has good supervisory bodies and adequate laws, but falls behind in their application.
In conversation for Aktuálně.cz, this is said by Miloslav Kala, Vice-President of the Highest Control Office (Nejvyšší kontrolní úřad, NKÚ).
"A law is never perfect, but it must be applied correctly - and I do not think that is the case with us," Kala comments on the current situation.
A similar result appears to be the result of joint control by Czech and German auditors.
As a negative example of practice, he leads Prime Minister Petr Nečas to the so-called "Black System".
Recently, the Prime Minister said that the ODS would not harass entrepreneurs with controls - is the system now banned or allowed?
"A law must have its validity, and if something is forbidden by law, then the chairman of the government cannot simply come, and the control office, whose duty is now once the control of the observance of the law, in its activity hinder", notes Kala.
At the meeting of the Control Committee of the Chamber of Deputies you spoke about a common Czech German project in which the laws of both countries regarding public procurement were compared.
What was it about in concrete terms?
This is a parallel examination which we started about two years ago.
Simply put, it is a question of the European legislature defining how public procurement is to be handled, on which the national legislation is based, and finally, there is the actual practical application.
All of this we compared with each other, and although the examination has not yet been completed, we have found very interesting differences. Generally speaking, the laws are perhaps even more "strict and perfect", but the actual application in Germany is better in some parameters.
This confirms that it is not enough to establish new and more precise rules over and over again, and it is also necessary to deal with the actual application of the law.
To what extent can the project be a help to you? What results for you from this project?
Such joint control could help us to stop constantly striving for the perfection of laws and the reduction and balancing of thresholds, if this does not seem to have a particularly positive effect.
Profitability means buying a thing at a reasonable price (which is not always the lowest price) and excluding unlawful enrichment or even criminal acts.
But the reduction of threshold values for orders does not guarantee that we will achieve this goal.
Perhaps it is even the case that in this way we will only burden the system with excessive 'paperwork', and those looking for gaps in the system will have much easier to exploit than if the thresholds were higher.
You are talking about the problems with the practical implementation of the Czech procurement law.
How does the control system in Germany work?
Is there a similar authority here as our NKÚ, or does the system work differently?
As far as the authorities are concerned, the German counterpart to the NKÚ is the Federal Court of Auditors, which has a similar structure to that of us and also has a college, which is only formed slightly differently.
The competences are also comparable to a certain extent, but Germany is a federal state, i.e. there are also these audit institutions in the individual federal states - in this the German system differs from ours.
The BRH may only control federal funds, which corresponds to our state funds.
Public funds, which are administered by the districts and municipalities, are subject to the control of the state accounting institutions.
As far as German legislation is concerned, is it easier than ours?
In general, I would be reluctant to compare this without concrete indications. Nevertheless, in some respects, Germany is often referred to as a model, but it certainly cannot be said that Germany is better in everything.
Is that perhaps because the examiners there are better?
This is certainly not, but as I said: I do not particularly like comparisons of this kind.
It should also be noted that those countries which are an example for us also have problems to contend with.
Otherwise they would not have any cooperation with our authority, right?
As far as Czech legislation is concerned, what significance did the amendment of the procurement law have for your authority, do you already feel any effects?
In view of the fact that this amendment is only in force for a short time, it has not yet affected our tests.
As our controls take place retrospectively, we have to expect a certain delay here.
Until now, we have seen more effects in the preparatory phase of future controls - we have introduced the new control instrument "Detection of risks of inefficiency" and analysed and analysed with this almost 14,000 public procurement - here the changes will naturally have an impact, as the thresholds change, the conditions for certain types of tenders have been modified, etc.
Do you see the adoption of this law rather positive, or is the system burdened with further bureaucracy?
I think that this law is certainly a step in the right direction and I hope that this assumption will be confirmed.
However, the problem may arise that the rules become 'stricter' and can no longer be respected.
Already under the previous rules, persons undergoing an audit vis-à-vis the institution (for example, in the case of an operational programme of regional policy, the Regional Council) are accountable to the effect that any failure to comply with the procurement law constitutes a breach of budgetary discipline.
Is it then useful to make the law even more stringent?
I do not think that way.
The system must exclude those who want to attack and abuse the system and not punish those who have committed a formal error that does not affect the actual decision-making process.
Such a system puts even greater pressure on bureaucracy.
