Šimon Ornest: At our concerts we want to collect positive energy
What do you think about the world going down in less than a month?
This is one of those disaster reports to which we people are so fond.
With our band The Tap Tap we ’ re more fun about it and say that we ’ re the only band in the world that can collect enough positive energy to stop or prevent world destruction.
In December you will also realize a unique project with three concerts against the end of the world.
Can you introduce the project to our readers?
It is a nationwide benefit event that we have been planning for two years.
For this we want to use the marketing potential of the Mayan calendar, the end of which is predicted for December 21 at 11: 10 in the morning.
On the day before, i.e. on December 20, three concerts will take place in Prague, Brno and Ostrava at the same time from 21: 00.
The end of the concerts is supposed to be about the time when the Mayan calendar ends on the Pacific island of Kiribati, which lies in a time zone around 12 hours before us.
From whom does this idea come?
Originally probably by me, then we designed the idea together with our graphic artist Honza Augusta.
Not only do we want to gather sufficient positive energy to prevent world destruction, but we also want to reflect together with the public on the state in which we hand this world over to our children.
On the occasion of the end of the Mayan calendar, we have also developed a unique collection of shoes, T-shirts, bags and keychains against the downfall of the world, with which the people can also support us with their purchase via www.e-tap.cz.
The band The Tap Tap has also recorded the so-called anthem against the end of the world with the title "Weltuntergang fällt aus" together with other performers.
Even today, the hymn is very popular on YouTube. Will it also resound at the benefit concerts?
Of course, and at the very end, provided that everything works out and that the end of the world does not take place...
The hymn is to be sung simultaneously by all performers at all three concerts.
In addition, the hymns will be broadcast live together by Czech television.
The text of the anthem comes from Tomáš Hanák, who also plays the main character of Jesus in the video clip, Xindl X sings with...
How did you come to work with them?
We also cooperate with other personalities of the Czech cultural scene, which is due to the fact that we realize many benefit events and concerts...
We strive to involve these people intensively in our projects.
It has been shown that most of us are interested in working with us and have fun.
What purpose does the proceeds of the concerts against the end of the world benefit from?
For the establishment of the barrier-free educational center Studeo, where we have been working together with the association Tap at the Jedlička institute for six years.
The students of the Jedlička institute are regularly supervised by lecturers who help them with various leisure activities.
Since the students themselves do not have the means to visit the lecturers, we would like to help them in this way.
As part of the completion of the Jedlička Institute, a separate building is to be built, into which we then move with this project.
Several groups and performers perform at each concert.
What criteria did you choose them?
We wanted to put together a programme that appeals to all generations, including children.
For example, Chinaski, Support Lesbians, Illustratosphere with Dan Bárta, The Tap Tap, Marián Bango and Jiří Suchý perform in Prague.
Further information can be found on the website www.kpks.cz.
Are similar "major events" planned for the future?
In May we will perform for the first time at the Prague Spring, and also for this concert we will prepare an interesting program with interesting guests.
Next year we would also like to perform in the Czech House in New York, and I personally - if we are already in the USA - would also like to combine this with performances in Washington and Chicago.
Your foreign plans are not very small, so far you have already performed in Madrid, Brussels, London or Moscow.
The Tap Tap, however, is a group composed of people with disabilities.
How do you manage these journeys logistically and organizationally?
It is not as bad as it seems at first sight.
Five of our members are wheelchair users, i.e. the wheelchairs must be transported in the luggage compartment. Furthermore, we have to carry many instrument cases and other luggage...
Nevertheless, so far it has always worked without problems, ČSA and British Airways were always very well prepared for us, that I have sometimes already wondered.
Even in Moscow, where we were recently, there were no problems.
By travelling abroad, you have a comparison of how accessibility in individual countries looks like, how people with disabilities can be treated there, etc.
How did you experience these things so far?
After Madrid, Luxembourg, London and other cities where everything works better than with us, we have just witnessed in Russia that everything is still in its early stages in the East.
Opposite Prague, Moscow is absolutely not suitable for disabled people. There, it is still unusual if someone is travelling alone in the city centre by wheelchair.
It is not even self-evident that a wheelchair driver is allowed in the elevator, for example.
Fortunately, clubs are also emerging there trying to point out the problems of people with disabilities.
And in what respect must we catch up with the more developed countries?
There are still many things in which we hang behind...
It should be noted, however, that improving the situation always depends on the efforts of those affected.
In London and Madrid it is absolutely common for people with severe disabilities to move independently in the public space, go to the museum, use toilets, etc.
But it is not exactly customary that a larger group of disabled people take an active part in social events there, in which we are a little ahead of the West with the band The Tap Tap!
Respect for the public and accessibility is one thing, but only when important athletes, artists, actors, politicians or lawyers come from our ranks will things really begin to change.
So far, these are only individual cases of particularly strong personalities.
The Tap Tap is currently very popular, but if we go back a few years, what motivated you to found a band in 1998?
At that time I started as a supervisor at the Jedlička institute, where I met many young people who were interested in dealing with something intensely.
And since I am a musician myself and play saxophone among others, I have founded a music group together with a colleague.
Well, and over time, as our moderator, Láďa Angelovič, used to say, it got out of control (laughs).
But the band became known only in the last years, or am I mistaken?
It is true that cooperation with well-known singers has helped us, and we have also begun to actively promote ourselves.
We have become aware that if one does something and this cannot be seen outwardly, one's own achievement does not exist in a certain sense.
Thanks to the EU funding, we can also afford good lecturers, high-quality equipment and so on.
Was it your goal to get it so far with The Tap Tap?
From the beginning, I have felt the potential that things can be tackled differently.
In the show business today often one copies the other.
This is logical in its own way, as everything new is considered with caution and accepted only after a long time.
There are few really unique things, and I dare say that Tap Tap is one of them.
The first impression that the viewer usually has is of course compassion; this is only natural...
But this compassion is absolutely superfluous, because people with disabilities are not lonely and abandoned beings that we should regret.
They are people who can live and develop a full-fledged life, provided they have the necessary means to do so.
I always say that if people with disabilities succeed, this is not just progress for themselves, but for the whole of society.
Was it also helpful for this success that you are a strict boss, as you hear from many people?
If you want to do something good, you must not compromise on many things and also demand a certain discipline.
However, I believe that this is completely normal.
Some come to us with romantic conceptions, and when they find out that they have to rehearse twice a week, complete preparatory phases and spend a lot of time on concert tours, then the enthusiasm goes out quickly among many.
But this is how it works everywhere, in every band that wants to work seriously and achieve something.
Currently, The Tap Tap has twenty members.
How many of them were there from the beginning, i.e. since 1998?
Only one: Láďa Angelovič.
We are an open group. People come and go. That cannot be prevented.
Who has the will and the desire to participate, is always welcome with us.
