Poland and Space.
Last week, Poland was accepted as the twentieth member of this space agency at a Council of Ministers meeting of the member states of the European Space Agency (ESA). Poland is thus the second member of the former Eastern Bloc (after the Czech Republic, which became a member of ESA on 12 November 2008).
Poland started a close cooperation with the ESA in 1994 and participated in several projects in the following years.
Poland ’ s journey into space began much earlier, of course.
Even before the Second World War, Polish cosmos enthusiasts were engaged in space travel, not always coming to understand it.
Here, for example, I recall the lecture given by A. Šternfeld in the Warsaw Observatory on 6 December 1933, in which the author presented thoughts from his pioneering work "Entrance to Cosmonautics".
However, the ideas of the young engineer (born in 1905) left the audience cold, and after years Šternfeld remembered that only Dr. Jan Gadomski had shown interest in his work.
Šternfeld won in 1934 for "Entrance to Cosmonautics" the Prix REP deer donated by Robert Esnault and André Louis Hirsch.
Dr. Jan Gadomski (1899 - 1966) later became an important advocate of astronomy and space travel.
In Polish magazines he published hundreds of articles and wrote several books on these scientific disciplines.
Gadomski ’ s worldwide recognized contribution to the development of space travel has been appreciated, among other things, by the fact that one of the craters on the earth side of the moon was named after him.
Already in 1925 a railroad Draisine was built in Poland, for which a rocket engine was planned.
The author of the draft and the details of this project unfortunately remained unknown.
It is not even clear whether the rocket should be used for starting or braking the draisine.
The information on this is exclusively from the contemporary press.
In 1933, the Polish infantry began to deal with rocket powered bullets.
The research was conducted by the Komórka Techniki Uzbrojenia Institute in cooperation with Prof. Mieczyslaw Wolfke and Prof. Gustaw Mokrzyckiegi.
It is clear from the documents handed down that research had penetrated to the stage of practical testing.
The research was then interrupted by the invasion of the German Wehrmacht.
In 1937, the draft of a photoelectric hunting rocket by Ing. Rohoziński appeared in the trade press, and in the following year, the work "Rakieta - torpeda powietrzna i rakietobomba lotnicza" by the author Leliwa and Krzywoblocky appeared.
Both projects dealt with the military use of rocket propulsion.
Shortly before the war, all projects for military use of rocket technology were coordinated by the Temporary Scientific Advisory Committee (Tymczasowy Committee Doradczo and Naukowy).
The committee was established in 1937, but after two years of work, its work was terminated from the start of the war.
Further articles on space travel appeared after the war thanks to the work of the Polish Space Society (Polskie Towarzystwo Astronautyczne) in the Polish press.
The first mention of this company is made in 1954 in the November issue of the magazine Problemy, in which four extensive articles of space travel are devoted.
The article by Prof. M. Subotowicz contains the proposal to establish a space society.
At the time, there were already the first projects on satellite technology, and it was foreseeable that exploration of space would have a future.
As early as 1956, the Polish space company PTA made an effort to join the International Federation of Space Aerospace, which was founded in 1951, and in fact already became a full member in the autumn of 1956.
The following year, the first PTA president, Kazimierz Zarankiewicz (1902 - 1959), became Deputy Chairman of the International Federation for Space.
He held this office until his death in 1959.
Since 1956, the PTA has been instrumental in the development of the extremely successful meteorological missile (Rakieta Meteorologiczna), the first Polish rocket for scientific research.
The first type, the RM1, was completed in 1957, the first start was on 10 October 1958.
The rocket with a maximum flight height of 1800 m was about 80 cm long and weighed not quite 5 kg.
Later an improved version, the RM 1A, was built, and in 1959 in the Błędów desert flight tests began with the two-stage rocket RM 2. more
The rocket was 1.4 m long and weighed about 11.5 kg.
A further stage of development should already be able to do real scientific work - the RM34 rocket should reach an altitude of up to 14.5 km and be used for the observation of height winds.
In 1962, however, the further development was discontinued.
Successor of the first rockets of type RM was the Meteor 1-missile developed in the years 1962 to 1965.
The rocket was designed as a two-stage rocket, its total length was 510 cm and the takeoff weight was 32.5 kg.
Three types of this rocket were developed (Meteor 1A, -1B and -1C), which differed from each other in the size of the transport space for scientific instruments.
The Meteor A1A rocket had a transport space of 0.4 litres capacity, Meteor A1B of 0.34 litres and Meteor A1C of 0.62 litres.
The maximum altitude of all three types was 37 km.
Between 1965 and 1968, the meteor missile was developed in the aviation institute. The first flight tests began in October 1970.
It had a take-off weight of 380 kg and was able to transport a payload of 10 kg to a height of about 60 km.
Afterwards the versions Meteor and Meteor were built.
The accession of Poland to the COSPAR (Committee for Space Research) in 1960, followed two years later by the establishment of a national COSPAR committee, is also worth mentioning.
Poland also participated in space research with Soviet satellites as part of the Intercosmos programme, and in 1978 the Polish pilot Miroslaw Hermaszewski became second intercosmonaut after the Czech Vladimír Remek.
