The movie Argo: When it's the worst, call Hollywood
In November 1979, a mob of demonstrating Islamist students occupied the US Embassy of Tehran and took 52 diplomats hostage.
For their release, they called for the extradition of Shah Mohammad Reza Pahlavi, who had fled to the US after the revolution, who for decades had preserved the patronage of his regime.
There was no positive way out of this situation for the American government - it could not afford to throw the Shah overboard, as this would have severely damaged the trust of its allies in other countries.
At the same time, it was unable to enforce the release of hostages in Iran, where the revolution led to the establishment of a theocratic regime.
It was a serious blow to the reputation of the united states, and the subsequent fiasco in the violent attempt to liberate hostages made everything even worse.
The diplomats captured were finally released after 444 days after negotiations had been mediated by the Algerian government.
The fate of hostages caused a wave of solidarity and anti-Iranian sentiment at home.
The Iran debacle contributed significantly to Jimmy Carter ’ s defeat against Ronald Reagan in the 1980 presidential election.
The film Argo by the director and actor Ben Affleck describes an episode of this story that gave the USA a small partial victory.
Immediately before the occupation of the embassy, six embassy staff managed to escape.
This ended after numerous complications in the residence of the Canadian ambassador.
The CIA, in collaboration with the Canadian authorities, managed to bring the refugees from Iran, helping them to cover up their true identity with an extravagant story - they traveled camouflaged with Canadian passports as members of a film staff who allegedly visited locations for a science fiction film in the country.
Combination of genres
The plan developed by Tony Mendez, the expert on "Exfiltration", also required Hollywood cooperation.
To make the camouflage credible, articles about this film project appeared in specialist magazines, press conferences were held, and the fictitious production company had a real office.
The details of this operation were kept secret for a long time and the film is based on the memories of Tony Mendez.
Afflecks Film is a special combination of several film genres.
On the one hand he is a realistic political thriller, but at the same time also a so-called "Caper Movie", i.e. the story of a successful hussar piece such as the film Ocean's Eleven.
As a result, the mood levels in the film alternate - on the one hand, the documentary scenes from Tehran (iconic contemporary photographs are shown in the title sequence, and there are no major differences in the film version of the same situations).
On the other hand the loose passages from Hollywood, which come ironic and slightly exaggerated.
And then there are scenes from the CIA headquarters and other institutions - men in suits at the meeting table, on the official corridors, on the phone...
Ben Affleck succeeded with this film a remarkable restart of his career.
A smiled actor has become a respectable director, and as an actor he is no longer the goal of ironic remarks.
Argo is his third feature film after the thriller Kein Kinderspiel (Gone Baby Gone, 2007) and the thriller Stadt ohne Gnade (2010).
At the same time it is Affleck's first film, which does not play in the director's home Boston.
The feeling for the atmosphere of the place belonged thereby to the characteristics, which the previous films of this director distinguished from the standard Hollywood.
Affleck also proves this feeling in Argo, where Tehran is "played" by Canada.
The best scenes of the film play in the streets and show the reconstruction of events that really took place - the input sequence of the storming of the message is very impressive in its clarity, yet conveying the feeling of confusion and unpredictability that occurs when the story moves somewhere.
Affleck and his team have a similar effect on fictional scenes (the wrong film wand on a bazaar in Tehran).
Too much action in too many places
The director also had to deal with the fact that the story actually does not offer many exciting scenes in the cinematic sense.
With the few, however, he works quite successfully, sometimes helping the reality something - which then does not always look so elegant (the scenes, in which the imminent crisis at the airport in Tehran is averted by a telephone call in America, or even the chase on the runway, seem somewhat artificial).
The weakness of Argo is its too wide dispersion, which is conditioned by the need to show too much action in too many places.
Alan Arkin and John Goodman are very charming in their roles as Hollywood co-workers, but their characters deserve more space, and thus they are far from alone in the film.
Affleck ’ s film thus loses some traction. It ’ s a film that can be followed with a certain interest, while gouting the design and the style of a 70-year-old thriller.
However, he hardly arouses enthusiasm.
However, as a reminder of a somewhat lively piece of history to this day, and as a proof of how exaggerated the ideas of the almighty and omniscient secret services are, it is sufficient.
Guidelines for inflating balloons, bananas and circus
The server www.bankovnipoplatky.com, which annually launches a survey on the most absurd bank charges, has decided this year to host the competition "Most absurd regulation or idea from the EU's workshop".
"This was the idea behind the recent EU plan to introduce 40% of women in the management of large European companies," said Patrik Nacher, who is responsible for organising this survey, to the newspaper Právo.
Among the nominated absurdities, for example, is the ruling of the European Court of Justice on the standardisation of insurance tariffs for men and women.
Until then, women enjoyed an advantage in life insurance because they are objectively lower risk for insurance companies.
"Other incredible ideas from the EU's workshop can be nominated by the end of this year.
The actual vote will then take place until the end of February 2013 ", Nacher informed.
The controversial EU Regulations include, among other things, the mandatory addition of bioethanol to fuels, which is consequently harmful to nature, and the prohibition of reliable mercury thermometers, just because they contain a relatively small amount of this hazardous substance, or the directive on the size of chicken cages, which made eggs much more expensive this year.
Criticism in the past also harvested the de facto prohibition of the use of the term "butter spread" or also the prohibition of selling conventional light bulbs.
Bananas must be 14 cm long
The EU's apparatus often decides under pressure from this or that lobby of trade and industry, whose demands are usually represented in Brussels by one or more member countries (for example, the Czech Republic is currently trying to impose the demands of Czech banks with veto threats).
Lobby interests were also behind the fact that bananas of the highest trade class in the EU must be at least 14 cm long and must not have a "curvature anomaly".
The European Commission defended itself with the argument that it was merely harmonising the inconsistent national standards that would hinder trade.
EU standards on fruit and vegetables have already been softened against the resistance of some countries by pointing out that the previous directives would lead to food waste.
A candidate for victory in this survey may be the EU Regulation last year, which, in accordance with balloons, must be provided with the indication that children under eight years of age are not allowed to inflate the balloon without the supervision of an adult.
The EU referred to an American study that, according to balloons, is the leading cause of child suffocation.
A similar restriction already applies to children up to 14 years of age when using fair flows.
There are also curious ideas at home
It is also relatively absurd to have a directive that concerns European officials themselves - anyone who has an official function in the EU must not use the name of Macedonia because of the sensitivity of the issue for Greece and must instead say FYROM (Former Yugoslav Republic of Macedonia).
In cooperation with the association of liberal economists Laissez Faire, the Bankovnípoplatky.com server nominated not only the above-mentioned absurdities but also the EU Regulation on the scope of food supplies in a Member State.
The EU thus set the maximum volume of food stocks on the day of our accession to the EU in the Czech Republic.
The Czech Republic then exceeded, for example, the fixed volume for canned mushrooms, for which we were threatened with a high fine.
The organizers of the survey were also impressed by the idea that certain countries should receive money for not having a sea, or by the idea of giving subsidies for applications for funding.
These ideas did not come from Brussels, but from Prague.
"We are disadvantaged by not having a sea.
We will apply for a refund from the EU ", said the then Minister of Agriculture Jaroslav Palas (ČSSD) in autumn 2004.
He argued that the grain harvest was very high and that the state camps were overcrowded as a result of the so-called intervention purchases.
As the Czech Republic has another way to sea ports, Palas believes that the EU should pay us hundreds of millions of euros.
The European Commission finally met with the Czech Republic to organise a tender for the purchase of cereals from countries that do not have access to the sea.
Funding for applications for funding was offered to the municipalities by the Ministry of Regional Development under the direction of Minister Pavel Němec (US Federal Republic of Germany), which was specifically intended to provide funding for the establishment of funding applications to Brussels.
EU: Bizarre Regulations are the exception
Regulations in the Member States, although they are easy to target criticism, the EU's efforts to regulate, and hence the effectiveness and development of the European Union as a whole, are, in some experts' opinion, more worthy of recognition.
According to these experts, a more serious problem is the EU funding for projects that have nothing at all in common with the deepening of European integration, but which have been forced by individual Member States in the budget negotiations.
Emotions in this country also evokes the fact that the Czech Republic, like other Member States in Brussels, has to fight for the right to use specific designations of traditional products and does not always win this fight.
After a six-year fight with Germany and Austria, the Czech Republic was able to defend the name "Olomoucké tvarůžky", the national rum (Tuzemský rum), whose tradition dates back to the 19th century, but our manufacturers had to rename it "Tuzemák".
The name rum may only be used for products from sugar cane distillate, not for products from sugar beet.
In the official list of products registered in the EU, the company of world-famous cheeses Feta and Gorgonzola, Lübeck marzipan or Parma ham now also includes Karlovy Vary rusks, carp from Pohořelice and Třeboň, or the hops of Saaz.
The Pardubice gingerbread or the Hořice rolls can breed with an EU brand.
