The MVRDV architects prove that the real adventures are not only in the head - using the example of Spijkenisse and the recently built Bücherberg - 2 photos
"I find the building funny, it looks futuristic, and finally there is something interesting to see again," says Lisette Verhaig, a passer-by at the roadside.
And Stefan Spermon, IT technician in a nearby large-scale business, says: "But, it's beautiful, the house."
But I wonder why we still need a library today.
All have Internet, iPad, and eBooks.
No one goes today voluntarily into one of these old style libraries, right?
Spijkenisse, a sleeping town in need of a visit just outside Rotterdam, is a strange record holder.
The 80,000 inhabitants of the municipality have the lowest rate of education in the Netherlands.
In order to counter this stupid circumstance, a few years ago they decided to contribute to general education and to rebuild the seven fictitious bridges depicted on the euro banknotes as nicely brushed reinforced concrete miniatures.
The success of the education offensive was limited.
And so the city fathers realized that there was only one way to master statistics: a library must come!
Winy Maas of the Rotterdam architectural office MVRDV, master of the daring bar diagrams and producer of funny, indeed often cynical buildings, took the matter with his usual serenity and appeared in 2003 to the competition for Hearing with five books under his arm and a grin in his face.
And while the jury looked around and shrugged, the cheeky Meuse stacked his exquisite souvenir of greatness to a pyramid and ended his actionistically supported speech with the words: "Dear municipality!"
So that is my proposal for the book mountain of Spijkenisse, for the so-called Boekenberg!
Nine years later, the 30 million euro mountain has been buried.
It is part of a revitalization project, which also includes underground parking, supermarket, post office and a few adjacent residential and terraced houses with a total of 50 apartments.
At the beginning of November the Bücherberg was awarded the second prize "Best Library of NL 2012".
The project is also nominated for the Dutch National Wood Award 2012.
This means that the faceless small town gate, which up to now had no more to offer than a post-modern pedestrian zone and an astonishingly ugly town hall, behind whose white facades one would be inclined to suspect a dairy factory to enrich a piece of contemporary architecture.
Above all, Spijkenisse now has the first public cultural building in the history of its existence.
The long way to the book
The first impression: book dorado under cheese bell.
There is indeed a lift that leads through the middle of the mountain massif, but the true spatial and reading pleasures open up when the topography is pedestrian.
The all-round glazed interior is bright and clear, the burnt clinker floor and the elegant street lamps speak the language of a public city square unmistakably.
The urban ambience is perfect.
You are already looking for park bench, dog and football playing boys and girls.
And everywhere books, books, books.
"Normally the bookshelves stand along the facade, and in the middle there is a large, dark room, which is usually uncomfortable and impersonal," says Winy Maas.
We have turned the classic room configuration upside down and put the reading area from the inside out.
The interior of the Bücherberg is cleverly used: in the middle are offices, Internet library, chess club, environmental center and building technology center.
A special joy are the black bookshelves, which are wall cladding, parapet, stainless steel railings.
Optics, feel and smell are foreign.
Even die-hard architects and civil engineers shake the head of the unknown building material.
"We wanted to work with recycling materials here," explains Joop Trouborst, project manager at the municipality of Spijkenisse, on request of the standard.
And so one day we encountered a suitable waste product from agriculture in a Frisian farm.
For many years, a millimetre thin plastic fleece has been used in greenhouses and on fields in the Netherlands as a root underlay.
This is cheap and time efficient.
The thin textile holds one, two seasons, then it is ripe for the bulky waste.
For the library, the fleece was pressed to four centimetres thick plates for the first time in these quantities.
Under heat and pressure, the so-called Landbouwplastic (KLP) turns into a dark, homogeneous, resilient material that smells a bit of new cars and a bit of sports shoes.
After 105 steps you reach the summit.
At the end of the almost 500 metres long hiking tour, the Literaturcafé not only offers a fantastic view of the city, but also rewards you with Dutch croquettes and potted fish trees.
They provide an atmosphere, but above all the right humidity in the literary mountains.
Donations for the new soul
"One would not believe it, but this house is despite the many glass surfaces a flagship project in terms of ecology," says Trouborst.
Heated and cooled with geothermal heat.
Although the Bücherberg stands under a glass lintel, even on sunny days the sun shines only briefly into the interior.
The wide wooden glue binders, which stand across the glass façade, serve as shading and capture most of the solar radiation.
The room climate is very pleasant.
The rest is done with fully automatic blinds.
Stefan Spermon, the initial skeptic from the IT industry, has already ventured into the new library.
Also Lisette Verhaig was already there.
And also the TCM teacher Cynthia Bogarde, who calls the Boekenberg even Spijkenisses "long overdue soul".
The reason: For the opening a few weeks ago every inhabitant was invited to donate a book from his personal stock.
This is intended to fill the optical gaps in the not yet fully equipped library - currently 70,000 pieces.
The concept has emerged.
The shelves are filled up to the top.
"Nothing is worse than a half-empty library," says architect Winy Maas.
"I think, thanks to our invitation, every inhabitant now has a certain relationship with this new house.
Everyone knows that his book is part of this building.
And if it is only to the ornament.
Thus MVRDV succeeded in the supreme discipline, which is called in the jargon of identity foundation.
Spijkenisse has written literary history.
As young and uneducated as it may be.
This is finally a starting point for identity.
Szabo: "Germans must play a bigger role"
Germany abstained from voting on the admission of Palestine.
According to Stephen Szabo, an expert on US and European relations, Berlin is thus balancing on a narrow diplomatic level.
Deutsche Welle: Earlier this week, Germany had initially signaled that it would vote against the request for Palestinian observer status at the United Nations.
But then Berlin abstained.
Why?
Stephen Szabo: Germany does not support what the Israelis have done in Gaza.
Now, however, Germany must be cautious about its special relationship with Israel.
At the same time, however, I do not believe that it supports the American position either.
Germany wanted to demonstrate its independence - but without being too critical of Israel.
During the uprising in Libya in March 2011, Germany also abstained on setting up a no-fly zone.
This was finally enforced by NATO.
Is it difficult for Germany to take a clear position on important international issues?
Yes, that is true.
This is because it is changing its foreign policy, away from a policy managed by the US, so to speak, towards a German foreign policy.
It is aggravating that Europeans do not have a coherent and uniform policy.
So the Germans find themselves between the fronts.
They are expected to play a more independent role, but they are not accustomed to that.
I believe they still touch on their role, but they are on the way to a more 'normal' foreign policy.
A foreign policy, as they have France or Britain.
What does a "normal" foreign policy mean from a German point of view?
It shows a willingness to take positions in national interests that are independent of those of the US or European partners.
I believe that German foreign policy is motivated by economic policy, that is, exports and relations with certain regions, such as Russia, China or the Middle East.
Germany ’ s economic interests are to a certain extent different to those of the other major powers and therefore Germany must protect its interests.
Did these economic interests influence the attitude in the Middle East conflict and the UN vote?
On the one hand, Germany has large markets in the Middle East, especially in the Gulf states.
It must therefore be careful not to upset the public, but also the elites, in the Arab countries.
That certainly plays a role.
But I would not want to attach too much weight to this either, that is not a completely one-sided relationship.
But it certainly plays an important role in German considerations.
Has Germany damaged its relations with the US by abstaining on important decisions, such as the vote on Palestine?
I believe that there is great understanding of the German position in Europe and even in the USA.
That is why I do not believe that this was such a dramatic break as on the Libyan question.
Perhaps Germany will even gain some respect with it.
Because it signals that it is taken seriously as an international player and that its interests must be considered.
There are different opinions in Europe on the Palestinian initiative.
The US, on the other hand, has made clear its support for a veto.
Are there any differences of opinion between the US and many European nations?
Due to American domestic policy, these differences have always existed.
I believe that the Obama administration has quite a secret understanding of the European position.
But due to the political situation here, the government cannot, of course, publicly support this position.
I believe that the real differences of opinion are not as great as they always seem.
If you look at Obama ’ s relations with Prime Minister Netanyahu, Obama is not so brightly enthusiastic about Netanyahu ’ s policies.
Is it difficult for Germany to reconcile its close relations with Israel and the US on the one hand and the position of the most important partners in the EU on the other?
I think that is exactly what makes it so difficult for the Germans.
It would, of course, be a little easier for Germans if there were a coherent and uniform European policy, which is not the case at present.
So they cannot be part of a broader line and must instead push things out of their own position.
That is what they are doing with the euro.
I believe that in future, Germany will play a leading role in pushing Europe to a European position.
Of course, this is not easy for Germany, already because of the relationship with Israel.
This has always been a sensitive issue.
But I believe that it is clear to the Germans that they must play a more independent role.
Does Germany see itself as an important international player - does Germany want to play a leading role at all?
Or does Germany still find leadership difficult?
Germany is not yet accustomed to it, it is still unpleasant and, for obvious reasons, it is still difficult for the country to play a larger role.
For example, when we look at the euro crisis, every time Germany assumes a greater role, various anti-German feelings become free.
This does not make it easy for the Germans.
This is actually the old problem: you do not want to be surrounded by hostile countries.
In this sense, Germany is in a much more difficult position than the US.
It must be susceptible to various neighbors and opinions, and that is not easy.
Now the influence of the US in European politics is steadily decreasing, but the EU is not filling this vacuum at the moment, who else remains?
The Germans will simply have to play a greater role.
Even if they don't like it, it is unpleasant to them and makes them even more unpopular - c'est la vie!
Stephen Szabo is Deputy Director of the Transatlantic Academy in Washington, Washington, where academics and policy experts from Europe and North America collaborate to explore the challenges of the transatlantic community.
Szabo is also a member of the German Marshall Fund, where he specializes in German politics, US foreign policy and transatlantic relations.
