What are the most important sexually transmitted diseases?
Bacterial STI include syphilis, chlamydia and trippers (gonorrhea).
Common viral STI are HIV, human popiloma viruses, herpes genitalis or hepatitis.
Felt louse and scabies belong to the parasitic STI.
Who are the main groups concerned?
Syphilis and trippers occur mainly in men who have sex with men.
At least four out of five of all syphilis reported in Germany are reported to be transmitted through sexual contact between men by the Robert Koch Institute.
In heterosexual adults, chlamydia infections, trichomonads, candidiasis, trippers, and human papiloma viruses are common sexually transmitted diseases.
The spread of HIV is comparatively low among heterosexual adults in Germany - nevertheless: Approximately 20 percent of the new HIV infections are accounted for by this group.
Chlamydia infections occur much more frequently among adolescents than among other population groups.
According to European surveys, three quarters of all infections affect young people aged 15 to 25.
Human poplar viruses are also common among young people.
How did the number of infections develop?
Not all sexually transmitted diseases are subject to notification.
The number of syphilis infection has more than doubled from 1697 diseases in 2001 to 3698 in 2011, according to the Robert Koch Institute.
The number of new HIV infections has been declining since 2007.
In 2011 there were around 2700 cases.
