The Prosecutor's Office alleges that Bradley Manning did not complain about mistreatment
The prosecutor ’ s office contradicts Bradley Manning ’ s accusations that he had been mistreated in prison
The hearing deals with Mannings time in the Quantico Military Prison, Virginia
The defence seeks to dismiss the indictment on the basis of harsh conditions of detention
The private US Army is accused of having stolen thousands of confidential documents
On Friday, the prosecutor ’ s office tried to find out that Bradley Manning, accused of the greatest disclosure of confidential information in U.S. history, missed several opportunities to complain about his alleged mistreatment in military confinement.
During a cross-examination of Mannings during a pre-trial hearing in Ft. Meade, Maryland, Maj. Ashden Fein said that documents on weekly visits made by prison officials during Manning ’ s nine-month detention period in Quantico, Virginia, had no complaints about his treatment.
One day before the cross-examination, which was held as a result of a request from the defence for the rejection of the indictment - Manning had already been sufficiently punished by the hard detention period - Manning had declared that he had considered the suicide in prison.
The US Army intelligence analyst arrested in June 2010 is accused of stealing thousands of confidential documents during his service in Iraq.
The material was then published by WikiLeaks on the Internet.
WikiLeaks has never confirmed Manning as a source of information.
At the hearing on Friday, Fein and Manning went through the forms that officials had completed following their meetings with Manning during his detention in the Quantico Military Prison, where he had been imprisoned from July 2010 to April 2011 under increased prison conditions.
The officials asked Manning questions and wrote his answers.
When Fein asked him about the forms on Friday, Manning admitted that he had judged the treatment by his guards as "excellent" and the treatment by the establishment as a whole as "very professional".
The forms, according to Fein, did not contain any complaints about abuse, although the officials had asked Manning directly about his treatment.
Manning replied that he had expressed his concerns orally and that the officials had discussed them with him and indicated that they were dealing with them. However, they had not been logged.
"They wrote (after discussing the concerns)" No problems ", and that did not necessarily mean that I said nothing at all," Manning said.
The judge, Colonel Denise Lind, also asked Manning why he did not complain about his treatment when he met with a committee in January 2011 to investigate the suicidal thankfulness he mentioned a few months earlier on a form.
Manning replied that his intention during this meeting was to have his observation status reduced to "prevention of injuries".
The military said it had assigned him this restrictive status - which is one stage under the suicide threat - to his and the protection of others.
"I wanted to convince employees that I was doing well and to get rid of the observation status for the prevention of injuries (...) in order to achieve a higher quality of life from my point of view," said Manning.
Manning pronounced his arrest and transfer to Kuwait on Thursday, where he was detained for nearly two months before being transferred to the Quantico naval base in Virginia in July 2010.
He said that he had considered suicide in Kuwait and had once become unconscious because of the heat.
Not being allowed to know what happened to him or to the outside world was burdensome.
"My world shrank to Camp Arafjon, on this cage together," Manning said on Thursday.
I thought I would die in this cage.
When he was transferred to Quantico, Manning spent most of his days in a small cell - at least 21 hours and often more than 23 hours - and without society.
He was allowed only one mattress, a blanket, flip flops, clothes and his glasses.
Manning said he had tried to stay in motion, because the day was forbidden to sleep or even to lie down.
He always had to sleep with light, which entered his cell from the outside.
When he turned around at night and guards could no longer see his face, they woke him up to turn back.
In January 2011, Mannings lawyer formally raised objections to Mannings ’ treatment.
Manning was transferred to Fort Leavenworth, Kansas, in April 2011.
On Friday, the judge Manning also asked for an accusation he had raised in his statement on Thursday - so he had to sleep one night naked in his cell in Quantico and stand naked in front of guards and other prisoners in a morning count.
Manning had said he had never had the opportunity to cover himself with his blanket during this count.
In the interview on Friday Manning stated that he had closed his guard's order to drop the blanket with which he could have covered himself. However, he admitted that no one had asked him to do so.
On Thursday Manning said that he was forced to sleep naked the previous night. He would have tried to show an official that he was not at risk to himself.
Manning told the official that he could have used his underwear or flip flops to hurt himself, but did not.
That night, Manning said, his underpants, flip-flops and glasses had been removed from his cell.
His lawyers hope that the judge will at least take his prison experience into account and drastically reduce his prison sentence should he be convicted at his trial before the military court, which is scheduled for the beginning of next year.
The defense has indicated that Manning will commit minor offences, while other charges considered too extreme are being challenged.
The continuation of the hearing is scheduled for this weekend and the prosecution is expected to justify the conditions of detention.
The Pentagon remains in its position that Manning has been detained in accordance with the provisions applicable to all prisoners under the highest security precautions in Quantico.
The charges against Manning include favoring the enemy, unlawfully publishing intelligence information on the Internet, transferring national defence information and stealing public property or documents.
If he is found guilty on all counts, he is threatened with life imprisonment.
My Mexican identity crisis.
Many people are forced to leave Mexico due to the lack of opportunities
Mexicans tend to blame emigrants - they remind them of difficult times, he says
Navarrette believes that Mexican Americans are trapped between two worlds
On a recent trip to Mexico, I had just crossed the hall and had arrived at passport control when perplexity was spreading in me.
Signs pointing to two queues: one for "Mexicanos" ("Mexicanos"), another for "Extranjeros" ("Aliens").
I stood there for a few seconds, unsure to which I should go.
I grew up in central California and was called "Mexicans" all my life.
An ethnic abbreviation - just as my friends in Boston call themselves "Irish" or my friends in New York "Italian".
Later I decided on "Mexican American".
But that was Mexico.
And in the home of my grandfather there was no need for abbreviations or hyphens.
I was just American.
I speak Spanish, at least good enough to maintain myself in this language at both ends of an interview.
But I do not have the vocabulary of a native speaker, and I do not get rid of my American accent either.
So I took my American passport and put myself in line for Extranjeros.
I thought about that moment this week when future Mexican President Enrique Pena Nieto visited the White House to meet President Obama.
The agenda included all the issues that are expected when the heads of these two countries meet: immigration, drugs and trade.
Pena Nieto was also very interested in talking about the growth of the Mexican economy, which is one reason why Mexicans today are equally likely to remain in Mexico instead of emigrating to the United States.
He wants to join forces with the United States and Canada and create a North American trading bloc modelled on the European Union.
And Pena Nieto swore to continue Mexico ’ s war on drug cartels, even though he did not mention any details in this regard.
Mexico ’ s relationship with the United States is complicated and full of resentment.
Most Americans are unlikely to waste a single thought that the United States invaded Mexico in 1848, forcing the country ’ s leaders to surrender more than half of their territory under a reserved gun.
But for Mexicans who think in centuries and not minutes, memories of this event cannot be overlooked.
So, as soon as a US government official criticises Mexico with even the slightest, complaints are heard - in the Mexican press and among the elites of the country - about how the Americans are oppressing the sovereignty of their neighbouring country.
And the children of Montezuma go on the path of war.
Yet Mexico ’ s greatest challenge lies in its relationship with the more than 35 million Mexican Americans living in the United States.
Fancy to talk about resentment?
There is more than enough.
Mexico has winners and losers. People for whom the country offers opportunities, and others for whom it does not.
The only reason why so many people of Mexican origin live in cities like Los Angeles, Las Vegas, Phoenix, Denver or San Antonio is that at one point in our pedigree a person - perhaps a parent or grandparent - did not get a chance in Mexico and emigrated to the north.
And in most cases this person corresponded to a profile - dark skinned, uneducated, from a poor village, etc.
We are the descendants of these people, and our faithfulness applies to them.
Not Mexico.
And although we may have now lived the American dream, attended good schools and received good jobs, we must never lose sight of the American dream we live - not the Mexican one.
Our identity may sometimes be blurred, but as far as our loyalty is concerned, this is not the case.
This clearly applies to the United States.
Furthermore, we are aware that many Mexican leaders do not like us.
This is based on reciprocity.
They see us as a memorial to a humiliating defeat and look down on us because we are not Mexican enough.
Our Spanish will never be good enough, our ties to Mexico will never be strong enough.
In their opinion, our existence is a symbol of failure.
If our families had not failed in Mexico, they would not have gone.
And then we would not be trapped behind the silk curtain - with a pleasant life in the United States, but somehow lost.
My wife, who was born in Guadalajara and legally immigrated to the United States as a child, reminds me that there are tensions between Mexicans and Mexican Americans, because Mexicans have a clearer idea of who they are - and Mexican Americans do so badly.
While she is an American citizen, she sees herself as part of two countries.
But many Mexican Americans, whom I know, feel that they are neither one nor the other.
We love the Mexican band Los Tigres del Norte, but also Bruce Springsteen.
One enjoys the best of both worlds, but is not rooted in any of them.
In Mexico we are seen as Americans.
And in the United States we are seen as Mexicans.
As I should learn during my trip, there is something that makes this relationship even more complicated: some Mexican leaders and parts of the educational citizenship want to resume their ties to the diaspora.
They want to use Mexican Americans as provisional "ambassadors" for Mexico, representing their interests in the United States.
We should tell our American colleagues how great a visit this country is and pressure on the political leadership to intensify its ties with Mexico.
Well.
That will not happen.
Too many injured feelings.
And, given the unfair distribution of income, unbridled corruption and drug violence, many of us are not at all sure that this is really a great country.
I fear you have to go alone, Amigos.
That is fair.
If at least some Mexicans are not yet prepared to forgive the United States for dealing with Mexico a century and a half ago, they must also accept that some Mexican Americans have resentment for how their family members were treated not so long ago.
Hmmm.
Maybe we are "Mexican" when I thought.
Old Battles, New Middle East
The ceasefire between Israel and Hamas could prove to be an unexpected pillar of peace
Can there ever be lasting peace between Arabs and Jews in the Middle East?
The latest bloody events seem to suffocate such hope in the bud.
In the midst of the usual blame, countless buildings have been thrown into rubble, more than 140 Palestinians, most of them civilians, and six Israelis killed - and for the first time rockets from Gaza have struck near the Israeli metropolis of Tel Aviv and the holy city of Jerusalem.
But, while Israelis and Palestinians seem trapped in their historic conflict, the Middle East is changing around them.
The Arab Spring has created a new, uncertain situation, and whether they want it or not - Palestinians and Israelis have become part of this confusion.
Perhaps this will only lead to more bloodshed.
But there are reasons to believe that the deadly stalemate could finally come to an end.
A war that is neither lost nor won
At first glance, in view of the current situation, optimism seems far from appropriate.
Even if the ceasefire agreed on 21 November continues, this week ’ s fighting has strengthened the hard-boiled on both sides.
The leaders of Hamas, the Islamist movement that has been controlling the Gaza Strip since 2007, will claim to have pushed back the Israelis, despite the fact that its group itself suffered huge losses.
Although several Hamas leaders are killed and the 1.7 million inhabitants of the Gaza Strip are enclosed in one of the most desolate and densely populated corners of the planet, Israel has not yet succeeded in destroying Hamas.
Indeed, Hamas is gaining in the West Bank, controlled by the rival, moderate Fatah Palestinian group.
And Hamas leaders could conclude that they have time on their side.
As Islamists have gained influence in the Arab world, Hamas has been able to draw powerful and rich friends to its side.
Turkey, a reinvigorating regional power once considered Israel ’ s closest Muslim ally, has seized the Hamas party – just like Qatar, one of the richest and most dynamic Gulf states.
Judging by Hamas, supporters believe that an Islamist crescent is formed around Israel – from Lebanon in the north, where militant Hezbollah has power, to Syria, where rebels may face Bashar Assad ’ s fall, to Jordan, where Hamas ’ s allies threaten the king.
And, in particular, the rise of the Muslim Brotherhood under President Muhammad Morsi in Egypt – the most populous and important Arab country by far – on the southern flank of Israel has changed the region ’ s balance in the long term.
Hosni Mubarak, the secular despot who ruled Egypt for 30 years until his fall in 2011, had little time left for Hamas.
By contrast, the brotherhood with Hamas is marginalized and its leaders are more dependent on popular views.
In future diplomatic negotiations, Hamas could prove to be an actor who cannot be pushed out by Israel and the United States.
The Israeli hardliners, on the other hand, draw an opposite conclusion.
From a military point of view, Hamas is no longer in danger.
The Israeli missile defence system, "Iron Dome", has proved itself and many of the Hamas missiles have been destroyed.
For at least a while Israel will be able to sleep calmer.
In diplomatic terms, the United States holds steadfastly to its position, and many European countries have blamed Hamas for the latest escalations of violence.
Israel has done well in recent years, particularly under Prime Minister Binyamin Netanyahu, who has largely ignored the peace process.
Although rockets from the Gaza Strip have killed about 30 Israelis since 2004, the country has remained relatively free from suicide bombers - not least thanks to the ranges that enter the West Bank and thus into the main part of a possible Palestinian state, which protect the Jewish settlements, which have been declared illegal under international law, but are constantly being expanded.
Netanyahu is in good shape. Avigdor Lieberman, in the run-up to the elections on 22 January, allied his Likud Party with an even more militant group.
Why also these deceitful Palestinians pacify and leave their own state to them?
If they really had control over the West Bank, would they not fire rockets, just like their counterparts in the Gaza Strip?
No, it is better to keep them in check behind the wall and punish them if they dare to lift their heads.
Perhaps the hardliners will be able to prevail, but the Arab Spring could get them through the bill.
Even if the Islamists, now in power in Egypt and in other countries, have little left for Israel, they will initially focus on domestic difficulties.
Israel ’ s defense act is greater than that of its four Arab neighbors together.
A war with the local superpower will hardly help the new Arab governments to repair their economies.
That pragmatic President Morsi met Barack Obama to achieve a ceasefire could be a promising sign - and perhaps symbolize the beginning of a new era.
Israelis should also think in the longer term.
While the rest of the Arab world is taking timid steps towards democratisation, Palestinians are still being deprived of their right to self-determination - a powder keg that will undoubtedly explode one day in the Israeli-occupied territories, just as a bus exploded this week in Tel Aviv.
The repression is already undermining democracy in the Jewish state, and with the growth of the Arab population, this situation will only worsen.
Bloody missions to push Hamas back in Gaza will increasingly demand diplomatic tribute over the years.
Both sides need an external impetus
The right answer is that represented by the more sensible representatives of both sides, the majority of the rest of the world, and by this newspaper: two states in which Israel assigns territories for security purposes.
The hope - small for the near future - is that the ceasefire will give outsiders more influence in enforcing this solution.
Egypt must now, together with Turkey and Qatar, stop arms deliveries to Gaza, and is better positioned than ever before to convince Hamas of the idea of a Jewish state based on the 1967 borders, supplemented by territorial exchange and a common Jerusalem.
External Arab nations should also persuade Hamas and Fatah to reach an agreement.
This would do more for the creation of a Palestinian state than with the forthcoming request for UN observer status.
Obama, too, must play his part in encouraging Israel to negotiate.
During his first term of office, he missed the idea of his own peace plan.
Far away in the white house it seems as if it is also averse to participation.
But that is a regrettable short-sighted perspective.
The United States has an essential interest in a stable Middle East.
This includes a peace agreement between Israel and the Palestinians.
Australian laws on uniform cigarette packaging enter into force
Health warnings and diseased body parts on neutral green packs that are the same for all tobacco brands
The world ’ s first laws for uniform cigarette and tobacco packaging have entered into force in Australia, replacing brand logos and colors with neutral, olive green lids, which are also printed with drastic images showing sick body parts and infants and children suffering from cigarette smoke.
Apart from the different health warnings and pictures, there is the only difference between the packs in the brand names, which are printed in identical, small font from Saturday onwards.
Australia is thus introducing the world ’ s most stringent rules on tobacco packaging.
The Australian Federal Government wants to dissuade young people from smoking by eliminating the glamorous image of tobacco consumption.
The government proceeds from studies that have shown that people who have not yet started smoking at 26 will no longer start with 99% probability.
"You can already see in children of young age that they understand the message that tobacco companies are trying to promote with their brand image," said Federal Health Minister Tanya Plibersek. She quotes studies that have shown, for example, that children associate the crown of a logo with the idea of a princess.
Although Australia has one of the least smoking rates in the world, and the changes will have little impact on the profits of multinationals, other countries are already considering similar steps.
The tobacco lobby fought hard against the laws.
It was said that the laws would favour black market trade, resulting in cheaper and more accessible cigarettes.
"The laws will lead to serious, unintended consequences," says Scott McIntyre of British American Tobacco Australia.
Chinese and Indonesian counterfeiters will offer far greater quantities of these products on Australia's roads.
Others say that the laws have boosted their business.
Sandra Ha from Zico Import Pty Ltd, a small family business, notes that demand for cigarette etui and silicone covers has increased enormously to cover unbearable packaging since British American Tobacco, Britain's Imperial Tobacco, Philip Morris and Japan Tobacco failed two months ago at the Supreme Australian Court to challenge the laws.
Zico has sold up to 6,000 units to wholesale stores and is waiting for new stocks.
For us, this is a good deal.
According to experts, the hooks in the popularity of social media are precisely the population to which the plan is aimed.
