The Australian government has banned internet advertising by local companies and sites, but has no influence on international sites.
"Those who market tobacco and have only one small area left to advertise their products will not get around the Internet," says Becky Freeman, a healthcare researcher at Sydney University.
On social media such as YouTube, Twitter and Facebook Freeman has found an increase in experience reports on trademarks written by "normal people".
One has to ask oneself the question: Is this merely a private person, who finds such a great favor to Marlboro and cigarettes, that she even takes a video for it - or does a marketing agency have to do with it?
British American Tobacco Australia says that instead of focusing on marketing, the industry is focusing on dealing with the new laws.
It has even gone so far as to pay Ukraine, Honduras and the Dominican Republic to challenge the new rules - those countries complain to the World Trade Organisation about unjust trade restrictions, although none of the countries trade more closely with Australia.
A WTO decision is expected in mid-2013.
According to Plibersek, the government has held talks with other countries that are considering similar packaging laws.
Canada was the first country to issue photographic warnings in 2001.
They have now been extended to more than 40 countries, including Brazil, Turkey and Ukraine.
Harder laws are being considered in Great Britain, New Zealand, South Africa and India.
Many Australian smokers are defiant.
The pictures do not affect me.
I just ignore them.
