"I used to use an hour to sort in a delivery, now I need four," says Yu.
"The government should have banned cigarettes completely - then we would have told ourselves okay, that's it, we make dense," he adds plainly.
In a constantly electrified world it is nice to be bored
This Thanksgiving I unexpectedly spent five hours at the airport when our plane failed due to mechanical problems and we had to wait for another plane.
So I had enough time to get bored with a few thoughts.
I don't want to lie.
Waiting for a flight at the airport for half a day is quite annoying - even if books, magazines and iPhones (and of course tax-free shopping) are available.
But more and more academics and child development experts are leading boredom as something positive.
If it goes after them, it is okay for us - and our children - to be bored occasionally.
In this way, the brain is forced to lose itself in interesting ways, which may promote creativity.
And because most of us today are almost constantly staring at one or the other screen, the benefits of boredom no longer benefit us.
So should we welcome boredom with open arms?
Yes.
And no.
I will come back to that again.
Like many people, I have always assumed that boredom is a relatively current phenomenon that has developed with increasing leisure time.
But Peter Toohey, professor of Greek and Roman history at the University of Calgary in Canada and author of "Boredom: A Lively History" (Yale University Press, 2011) does not see this.
"In fact, boredom has a very long history," he says.
The house walls of Pompeii decorate a Latin graffiti about boredom, which dates back to the first century.
And then there is the question of how we actually define boredom.
According to John D. Eastwood, an associate professor of psychology at the University of York in Ontario, Canada, the problem is that boredom has been defined and discussed in many ways.
After a long reading of research literature and the presentation of the idea in front of a focus group of about 100 people, Professor Eastwood and his colleagues came to the conclusion that boredom can be defined as the experience of "wanting to do a satisfactory job, but not being able to do this".
Boredom differs from apathy in that the person is not busy, but wants to be.
In apathy, however, there is no urge to do anything.
The key experience of boredom, he says, consists in a "disturbance of the attention process, paired with bad mood and the feeling that time is only slowly passing away".
Boredom can almost sound like depression.
But Professor Eastwood believes, although these two states may be related, bored people see the problem in their environment or the world, while depressed people see the problem in themselves.
Sometimes we believe that we are bored, even if we have difficulty concentrating.
In her study "The Unengaged Mind: Defining Boredom in Terms of Attention" - in German, for example: "The Inactive Mind: The Definition of Boredom under the Attention aspect", which appeared in September in the journal "Perspectives on Psychological Science", Professor Eastwood and his colleagues point to an earlier experiment in which participants listened to a volume on which a person read a magazine article.
Some groups heard a loud TV program from the neighbouring room that had nothing to do with the content. Others listened to it at low volume, so it was hardly perceptible, while the third group did not hear these sounds at all.
The people who heard the barely audible television said that they felt more boredom than the other two groups - they had problems concentrating, could not find any reason for them and attributed their difficulties to boredom.
If one tries to concentrate on a difficult or exhausting task, the disturbance of attention can lead to boredom, says Mark J. Fenske, associate professor of neuroscience at the University of Guelph in Ontario and one of the authors of the study.
On the other hand, if you perform a monotonous activity - "just like looking for faulty products on a factory conveyor belt, music can distract and help not to feel bored".
In fact, he says, we now know that gnashing and scribbling, often interpreted as a sign of boredom, can even combat them by keeping people physically more attentive.
"Studies have shown that children who are allowed to stamp around learn more and keep more information than those who are forced to sit still," Professor Fenske said.
We all get bored at some point - my delayed flight, a droning loudspeaker, a particularly tiring film.
But some people get bored lighter than others.
In order to measure these differences, researchers developed a "long term susceptibility scale" in the 1980s.
On the scale you will find statements like "Many things I have to do repeat themselves and are monotonous" and "I have so many interests that I don't have enough time for everything".
Using such scales, researchers have found that boys become bored more often than girls, according to Stephen Vodanovich, professor of psychology at the University of Westflorida - especially when it comes to the need for more and greater diversity of external stimuli.
But in general, teenagers are a pretty tense bunch.
In 1991 Reed Larson, professor of human and community development at the University of Illinois, conducted an experiment in which he contacted almost 400 teenagers and their parents seven to eight times a day with a pager.
He found that 32% of adolescents were bored in school and in doing homework, while 23% said they were bored if they were not in school.
But only 3% of parents said they felt bored.
Today, 21 years later, Professor Larson says that he does not know whether the percentage of boredom has increased or decreased.
He is certain, however, that "the youth is perceived as particularly boring", mainly because children and teenagers have no great influence on their daily routine.
So back to my question of origin: Is boredom healthy?
Sometimes not, because in extreme cases it leads to people taking extreme physical risks and falling into gambling or drugs to alleviate them - studies have shown that.
On the other hand, many philosophers and authors examine the relationship between boredom and creativity. Professor Vodanovich, who has been researching the subject for more than two decades, is of this opinion.
"With boredom, the brain wants to tell you that you should do something else," says Gary Marcus, Professor of Psychology at the University of New York.
But the brain does not always know what to do best.
If you are bored and you use this energy to play guitar and cook, you will be happy.
But television may create a sense of happiness in the short term, but it may evaporate in the long term.
So if an iPad is enough for his bored child, it can lead to boredom. However, it has not learned to entertain or control himself, says Professor Fenske.
And he adds: "Self-control transfers itself from one situation to the other".
The child not only learns to talk, but also gets more self-control in other areas.
I do not believe that we should celebrate boredom.
Nor should we be too critical of them.
Instead, our goal should be to make us feel at home, even outside the constant need for activity and technology.
Professor Eastwood agrees.
"It sounds as if we should be bored more often. But boredom is the tormenting, ceaseless desire to do something meaningful," he says.
He believes that the truth is that people are only looking for a way to switch off and relax.
"In an environment where we are constantly overstimulated, it is difficult to deal with when the noise is silent."
