This is the case with Anto Wijaya, one of the 400 miners who earn their lives by getting sulphur from the volcano Kawah Ijen in the east of the Indonesian island of Java.
For this purpose, he has to climb down to the bottom of his crater every day, where the sulphur gas flowing out of the earth solidifies in contact with the air.
After breaking out large sulphur stones, which can weigh up to 70 kilos in total, he transports them in two bamboo baskets on his shoulders over the steep paths of stone.
It is only 250 meters to the top of the volcano, which rises to a height of 2386 meters, but the exhausted carriers need more than 40 minutes for the ascent in the turtle pace, keeping the balance and putting their steps carefully so that they do not slip and crash.
They know that every step can cost their lives, as happened to a French tourist who crashed years ago on the steep slopes of the Kawah Ijen.
The miners of Kawah Ijen earn 5 Eurocent for every kilo of sulphur they extract.
