The company is PT Candi Ngrimbi, who has been using the volcano since 1960 and (never better) his workers to whom she pays 662 Indonesian rupees (5 Eurocent) for every kilo of sulfur.
This is sold to the petrochemical industry for 10,000 rupees (83 Eurocent) each, because this mineral is widespread in everyday life and is used for the production of matches, fireworks, cosmetics, dynamite and even for bleaching sugar.
"Since we normally carry 70 kg, we get about 46,000 rupees (3.8 euros) for each way," Anto explains, who normally does three routes a day.
For each route he needs three hours, after which he is completely done, but at the end of the day he has 138,000 rupees (11.5 euros) together.
What looks like a miserable reward for such an almost inhumane effort, however, is the triple of what he would earn from field work.
"The daily son of the miners here, where 15,000 rupees (1.2 euros) are paid a day during the coffee harvest and the average monthly income is two million rupees (167 euros), is very high," explains the carrier, who previously worked as a bricklayer on the tourist island of Bali.
There he earned 75,000 rupees (6.2 euros) a day, and the work was not so hard, but Anto returned with his family to Banyuwangi, a nearby village, for a reason that is as important in Indonesia as sulfur: "I have married a girl from Bali, where they are Hinduists, and I have brought them to Java to convert them to Islam".
Anto has asthma, breathing with difficulty, coughs frequently and his eyes are irritated because of the toxic gases.
The 27 year old Anto has been jeopardising his life at the Kawah Ijen for three years, whose sulfur has already left his first marks, although he covers his face with a mask and special glasses.
Anto has asthma, breathing with difficulty, coughs frequently and his eyes are irritated because of the toxic gases from the volcano.
This is the price he has to pay for reaching his dream.
