Conclusion of the Unasur Summit without publication of the Lima Declaration
The 6th Summit of the Presidents of the Union of South American Nations (Unasur) ended today in Peru without publication of the Lima Declaration, which was previously announced and was to be signed theoretically by the seven leaders present.
Efe repeatedly tried to gain access to the signed document at the 6th Ordinary Session of the Heads of State and Government of the Unasur. Sources in the State and Presidential Chancellery initially announced that they would hand it over after the Closing, but then declared that it would be published at some time on the website of the Peruvian Government.
When asked about the text, they stated that the content was presented to the press by the President of Peru, Ollanta Humala, for short explanations.
Journalists' access to information about the summit was limited at all times.
During the day, only the picture of the Presidential Meeting without sound was transmitted in the press room with the message "private session, limited audio".
The few information circulated among the journalists was received by the press speakers of some of the Unasur governments present at the meeting, but not by the Peruvian spokesman.
The only document that was distributed during the day was the list of participating presidents, causing discomfort among hundreds of journalists from various national and international media who demanded more information.
After that, the Peruvian Presidency sent the media an E-mail with the Summit's "Final Declaration", but it was the Humala Declaration and not the official document to conclude the Summit.
Last October, Peru hosted the Third Summit of South America - Arab States (ASPA), and on this occasion, too, the so-called Lima Declaration, which had been announced earlier, was not published, despite a strong press call.
On the official website of the ASPA you can see that the document was published last Tuesday.
At both international meetings, the Peruvian authorities stressed that the information systems were available to journalists, but that they restricted access to information to a large extent.
The summit also ended with the joint commitment of Chile and Peru to adopt a judgment of the Court of Justice of The Hague, which resolves a border conflict between both countries.
The presidents of Peru, Ollanta Humala, and Chile, Sebastián Piñera, met during the regional meeting and confirmed that they would accept the decision of the ICJ, which begins in The Hague on Monday, in the trial that Lima launched against Santiago, to listen to the pleas of both sides.
"We will follow and execute the judgment on the differences that we are currently bringing to this international court," Humala said together with his Chilean counterpart.
"Chile was, is and remains a country that adheres to international laws, seeks peaceful solutions to disputes, concludes agreements and submits to international courts," adds Piñera, and greeted Humala with a handshake in front of the flags of both countries.
Both presidents confirmed that they would submit to the ICJ after Colombia had brought an action against the Bogota Agreement following a decision on the maritime borders with Nicaragua, which considered it to be a serious mistake, in which it agreed to submit to the judgments of this international court.
The summit was attended by the presidents of Brazil, Dilma Rouseff, Venezuela, Hugo Chávez, Bolivia, Evo Morales, and Argentina, Cristina Kirchner.
Paraguay, which has been excluded from the Unasur since 2011 after the resignation of its president Fernando Lugo, did not attend the meeting.
The host President Ollanta Humala opened the talks in the morning and ended the summit meeting shortly after lunch in Lima.
The head of state read the final document in which it reported that 16 decisions were taken and that the lines of action for 31 projects between the South American countries were set for an investment of a total of 17 billion dollars.
On the decisions taken, he said that the countries of the Unasur will take "significant steps towards the goal of South American citizenship, to which we are extending the decisions on residence rights."
It announced that measures would be taken to "improve cooperation in the fight against insecurity in cities and against organised cross-border crime, as well as measures to improve access to medicines and the Internet at low prices in all areas of South America and to act jointly and efficiently in the event of natural disasters".
With the crisis in Europe, "economic consolidation (in Latin America) must not be triumphant, but should serve to expand our output and show our peoples a better future," Humala added.
"We have decided to give priority to a series of 31 emblematic projects aimed at improving the geographical links in South America, particularly in rural and border areas... and thus unite our countries and open up new economic forms," said the Peruvian President in a statement.
Among these projects would also be five Peruvian, located on the transverse axes of its territory from the coast to Brazil, and two of which would provide a better connection with Ecuador, although it did not give any further details.
The final document also referred to the political situation in Paraguay.
"We hope that the electoral process in this country will serve for its resumption in the Union of South American Nations", from which it is currently excluded.
The need for Latin America to remain an integrated region for prosperity and peace and good neighbourly relations was another aspect highlighted at the summit.
In this sense, the President of Colombia, Juan Manuel Santos, said before the start of his participation in the regional meeting that on Saturday in Mexico he expected a meeting with his counterpart of Nicaragua, Daniel Ortega, in order to treat the maritime conflict respectfully after a judgment of the ICJ called into question by Bogota.
"Perhaps I will meet President Daniel Ortega tomorrow (Saturday)," Santos said.
"We will review all these paths - they are not exclusive, and the agreement with Nicaragua also necessitates talks with Nicaragua," he underlined.
"I hope to be able to tell President Ortega that we will treat this matter as civilised and as respectful as possible," Santos added.
Santos and Ortega would meet in Mexico on Saturday, where they intend to attend the inauguration of the new president of that country, Enrique Peña Nieto.
As part of the summit, the defence ministers of the bloc met ahead of the summit to adopt the 2013 plan of action to strengthen dialogue and consensus on the defence of the region.
Argentina, Bolivia, Colombia, Ecuador, Peru, Brazil, Uruguay, Venezuela, Chile, Guyana, Surinam and Paraguay are members of UNASUR, even if the latter country is currently excluded.
Peru presided over the regional bloc.
