Fabrizio was 21 years old when the result of the investigation was confirmed: HIV positive.
"It was as if a bomb hit," he says about the moment when he received the diagnosis that the doctor "tried to weaken" without noticeable success.
He hid it from his family.
He decided to take care of his illness alone and began to inform himself about it; and this with such commitment that he just celebrated his 43rd birthday.
He is undoubtedly one of the oldest patients of the HIV unit of the Hospital Civil de Guadalajara (HCG), into which he came after several fights in 1994.
Fabrizio has been living with the human immune deficiency of HIV for 22 years, which was hard to imagine at the beginning of the 1990s, when there were many doubts, few treatment options and more stigmata.
At that time, even the director of an IMSS clinic avoided saying goodbye "because it led to a dead end."
At that time, AIDS was synonymous with death.
Today it is possible to survive this syndrome with quality of life.
However, many people still come to the clinic who know nothing about their disease and where the virus has already done damage and has exhausted their immune system, and who are victims of opportunistic infections.
31 years after AIDS appeared in the world, i.e. after the occurrence of the first reported cases, "the great success today means that the survival of a patient receiving treatment in good time and the survival of the general population are exactly the same," said the head of the HCG's HIV unit, Jaime Andrade Villanueva, saying that this information was supported in April this year by a respected scientific publication.
The specialist for infectious diseases and HIV / AIDS, Andrade Villanueva, commented that since 2008, the scientists concluded that while AIDS was not a death sentence, the years of survival and quality of life depended on the degree of impairment of the immune system of persons at the beginning of the treatment, and that those who are not drug dependent had greater chances: up to 30 years with a count of 200 CD4 and 50 years with a count of 500 CD4.
Simply put, the above remarks mean that those who receive positive diagnosis of HIV at the age of 25 can "easily become 75 years old as long as they are under control", said the skilled person.
In order to be able to correctly classify this progress, it must be remembered that the life expectancy of Mexicans today is on average 76 years.
Even if mortality has decreased significantly in recent years (in Mexico, the number of people dying of AIDS has decreased from 6,678 cases in 2007 to 4,862 in 2011 (ONUSIDA annual report)), it is still true that 60% of patients registered in the national database have died since AIDS appeared.
In Jalisco alone, 255 people died in 2011, and by May of this year, there are already 187 deaths; however, it is assured that there has been universal access to antiretroviral medicines since 2005.
- So why do people still die from it?
- In my opinion, the problem is not access to treatment.
This is my opinion, and so is in our hospital.
At least in the past 12 years we have had no supply problems with the drugs. The problem is that people come in a far more advanced state because they do not know their infection state, i.e. in very late stages of the disease.
He makes a striking statement: "Nine out of ten patients come to us if they already have an accompanying infection. In order to be able to influence global mortality, more early diagnoses are required, which is why all persons who need this must be offered massive detection tests."
The experts and officials of the Consejo Estatal de Prevención del Sida en Jalisco (Coesida) (State Committee on AIDS) and the patients like Fabrizio, who carried out his test at a private laboratory, are in agreement with this proposal, for the only reason that it had been done by a friend of him who, despite his young age, was already in the AIDS phase and even had the Kaposi -sarcoma (a cancerous tumor), which is one of the usual complications.
Everything is different when you know that you have AIDS.
Some think they will die and don't want to hear anything.
"If I already have to die, then I prefer to burst three times", they say in my case.
The change was towards improvement, I feed myself well, exercise and take the medication.
Today his parents only know that he had cancer.
I live a normal life, like everyone else.
"I work, do a lot, have an active but responsible sex life, I pay attention to my health and that of the other person," says Fabrizio, who agreed to share his intimate details with MILENIO JALISCO in order to animate with his testimony those who are afraid today within the framework of the worldwide AIDS Day.
They should test if they belong to the risk group. The sooner they know whether they are HIV positive, the better, and if they already know the diagnosis, they should learn how to live responsibly like all people.
His news is a summary of the fight against AIDS in 2012.
Condoms behind the counter
There are big holes between health programmes and ordinary citizens, Ricardo Salazar, journalist from Guadalajara, who has taken up the cause of HIV, explains.
And the most important thing is prevention.
In the places "the distribution of condoms was actually increased; in the past they were given individually, now they give us packages with a hundred pieces, which is already good, but there are still people who do not have access to a condom," he said.
Young people are among the risk workers for new infections.
"Why do you need this?" is a widespread mockery of social workers, orientation personnel in schools, employees in pharmacies and in the health system who do not want to expose themselves to young people, the correspondent assured.
He suggested reorienting this inefficient distribution; the condoms should not only be behind the counter, but also in outputs in public toilets of facilities that are often visited by young people.
Promiscuity should not be promoted.
They should not be paid for the beer and motel, as Governor Emilio González replied to the question of whether pre-conservatives would be distributed under his administration.
"Sexuality does not look like this; it is best to bring the condoms closer to those who already do a sexual activity," he summarized.
Key data of Jalisco
There are 13,435 cumulative cases (12,158 AIDS and 1,317 HIV).
The state is nationally 4th in new and cumulative AIDS cases, and 13th in terms of HIV.
92% of contagious cases occur via sexual intercourse, 6% via blood and 2% perinatal.
It is estimated that 50,000 people live with HIV because there are 4 or 5 people who do not know each case.
