Larry Hagman, whose role as the oil magnate J.R. Ewing in the television series "Dallas" became a symbol of the greed of the 80s, is dead.
He was 81 years old.
Hagman, who came back this year as J.R. in a new season of "Dallas", died Friday afternoon due to cancer complications according to a family press release from The Associated Press by Warner Bros., producer of "Dallas".
"Larry was back in his beloved birthplace, Dallas, where he once again played the iconic role he liked most," said the family.
The family of Larry and his closest friends were with him in Dallas for the celebrations of Thanksgiving.
Linda Gray, who played the role of his wife in the original and subsequent series, was with Hagman when he died in Dallas Hospital, her journalist Jeffrey Lane said.
He made joy to all who knew him.
He was creative, generous, funny, funny, loving and talented, and I will miss him very much.
"He was an original person and lived life to the fullest," Gray explained in a message.
Hagman was diagnosed with cirrhosis in 1992, and he admitted that he had drunk a lot for years.
In 1995, a malignant tumor was detected in his liver, and he underwent transplantation.
